<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Imports Decline Due to Currency Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's imports have
decreased by 70 percent due to continuing decline of the rupiah
against the U.S. dollar, general chairman of the All-Indonesia
Importers Association, Amiruddin Saud, said here today.
</P>
<P>
"Indonesian imports, including capital, raw and auxiliary goods
needed by domestic industries, have decreased by about 70 percent
due to the monetary crisis," Saud said.
</P>
<P>
Imports have dropped from 2.5 billion dollars per month before
the crisis to 750 million dollars per month, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the fall in imports will not disrupt the
activities of the country's export-oriented industries in the
short term as they have stocks which they could rely on until
February.
</P>
<P>
"If the government is too slow to overcome the currency crisis,
domestic industries, such as the textile industry, might face
risks in the long run," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Food, beverage and cosmetic importers might also be put in an
unfavorable situation, he said, adding that producers plan to cut
their imports.
</P>
<P>
Saud called on the government to continue intervening in the
money market to overcome the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The government has 20 billion dollars worth of foreign
exchange, enough to import goods in the next five to six months.
</P>
<P>
The country's currency, the rupiah, stood at 3,865 to a dollar
on Monday. Several money changers however traded the dollar at
about 4,000 rupiah.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah has dropped by about 50 percent against the U.S.
dollar since January this year following offshore speculative
attacks on the currency and a rush by local companies to hedge
their foreign borrowings.  
</P>
</TEXT>
