<HEADLINE> WHO Activities in Iraq Continue Despite Recent Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization
(WHO) will continue its activities in Iraq after the WHO premises
in the Iraqi capital of Baghdad were attacked by four unidentified
gunmen, a WTO official said here today.
</P>
<P>
The attack happened at about 7:30 p.m. local time on Saturday
when the gunmen disarmed the guards at the WHO office in Baghdad,
the organization's Deputy Director General Dr Fernando Antezana
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the gunmen then shot and threw hand grenades at the
houses, damaging several vehicles and and breaking house
windows. One of the four gunmen was accidentally injured during
the attack and was caught by Iraqi police. The other three fled.
</P>
<P>
There were no WHO staff in the compound when the attack erupted.
The Iraqi police investigating the incident suspected that the
attackers were "Iranian elements", the WHO official said.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the WHO said that it will continue its
collaboration with the Iraqi Health Authorities in the
implementation of its regular cooperative health program with
Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
