<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Discusses Bosnia Issue With Top Mission Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 8 (Xinhua) -- NATO Secretary General Javier
Solana together with NATO ambassadors today discussed the latest
developments in Bosnia with top officials of international
missions in a long session and in great detail.
</P>
<P>
At the session were International High Representative Carlos
Westendorp and Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe
(OSCE) chief representative Robert Frowick.
</P>
<P>
The NATO chief told a post-session press briefing that the
Dayton peace process was moving forward as demonstrated by the
Bosnian municipal elections that went without a hitch on September
13 and 14.
</P>
<P>
He said that not only new local authorities would be
established but important decisions had been taken regarding the
local media as well.
</P>
<P>
On October 1, NATO-led multinational Stabilization Force (SFOR)
troops captured, at the requirement of Westendorp, four radio and
television broadcast transmission towers from the hands of
pro-Pale Bosnian Serbs and promised to hand them over to the
supporters of incumbent Republika Srpska President Biljana
Plavsic.
</P>
<P>
"These signifies that something is going to change on the
ground," said the NATO chief.
</P>
<P>
The military alliance discussed the future of the SFOR at an
informal meeting of its defense ministers in Maastricht, the
Netherlands, on October 1 and 2.
</P>
<P>
The NATO ministers reached consensus that NATO would skip the
scheduled 50-percent phase-out in the run-up toward next June when
the SFOR mandate expires.
</P>
<P>
They are expected to discuss and decide in December on whether
the SFOR stays in Bosnia after June 1998.
</P>
<P>
Solana stressed that the way Bosnian Serb paramilitary police
forces had been dealt with demonstrated the change on the ground
as well.
</P>
<P>
SFOR troops rounded up several pro-Radovan Karadzic police
stations and a police academy for illegally bugging the telephone
communication of Republika Srpska President Plavsic and hoarding
away such heavy weapons as bazookas.
</P>
<P>
Light and heavy weapons were confiscated from the police
stations on the grounds that they are not to be used for policing
purposes.
</P>
<P>
Westendorp told the press that the situation in Bosnia now was
a critical one as the international community was helping Bosnia
establish a pluralistic media.
</P>
<P>
"A lot of progress has to be done before we can assess for how
long the presence of NATO and non-NATO troops is necessary in that
country," said the international high representative who is
coordinating the civilian side of the Dayton peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
The Spanish diplomat likened Bosnia to a patient just coming
out of the life-support system but still in the intensive care
unit.
</P>
<P>
"The patient will survive but we don't know how long this
intensive care will be necessary," he added. "So for the time
being it is clear to us that the security environment created by
the SFOR is needed to stay even longer than June 1998."
</P>
<P>
Frowick expressed the appreciation of the OSCE for the support
of NATO and the integration of the SFOR with the OSCE to see to it
that the Bosnian municipal elections were safe.
</P>
<P>
He said that the OSCE did have a decision on preparing for the
Bosnian parliamentary elections slated for November 23.
</P>
<P>
The OSCE representative said that the patient did need the
attention, hinting that his organization needed the backup of
NATO-led SFOR troops just as they did at the previous elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
