<HEADLINE> Japan Hopes Better Ties With DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto today expressed the hope that Kim Jong II's formal
election as the general secretary of the Workers' Party of Korea
will help improve relations between Japan and the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto told reporter at his official residence that he
expects bilateral negotiations at the level of deputy bureau chief
to head toward improvement, Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Foreign Minister Keizo Obuchi issued a statement,
saying that Japan cannot make immediate judgment if there will be
any change in DPRK's policies but will closely watch the situation.
</P>
<P>
"The Japanese government will continue its efforts toward peace
and stabilization in the Korean Peninsula." Obuchi said.
</P>
<P>
At deputy bureau chief talks in Beijing in late August, Japan
and DPRK agreed to resume ambassador-level talks for the
normalization of diplomatic relations at the earliest
opportunity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
