<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Adopts Policy for Electronic Commerce Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission today
adopted a policy framework concerning security on electronic
commerce, especially transactions on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
The executive body of the 15-nation European Union has decided
to pass into law the network security framework in the first half
of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The framework is aimed at ensuring the functioning of the
internal market for cryptographic products and services,
establishing a European framework for digital signatures and
stimulating a European industry for cryptographic services and
products.
</P>
<P>
Though rapid and efficient for worldwide communication
exchanges at low cost, open networks such as the Internet also
fall prey to such insecurities as intercepted and manipulated
messages as well as denied documents.
</P>
<P>
Encryption is necessary for electronic commerce because
consumers and financial institutions need to be confidant that no
one can tap into a transaction.
</P>
<P>
But the same encryption techniques can also be used by
terrorists, child pornographers or drug dealers to avoid arrest.
</P>
<P>
Divergent legal and technical approaches in different
countries, however, constitute a serious obstacle to the formation
of the internal market of the 15-nation union by hindering the
development of new economic activities linked to electronic
commerce.
</P>
<P>
Commission officials said today that Europe is going to use,
unlike the United States, unlimited encryption even though the
technology can benefit criminals.
</P>
<P>
Though the policy paper did not specifically refer to the U.S.
global push for encryption, one commission official familiar with
the policy framework said that the plan can be rightly interpreted
in principle as a counterproposal.
</P>
<P>
Commission officials argued that widespread availability of
encryption can also prevent crimes.
</P>
<P>
The damage caused nowadays by electronic crime, in the form of
industrial espionage, credit car fraud, toll fraud on cellular
phones and piracy on pay TV encryption, is estimated in the order
of billions of ECUs each year.
</P>
<P>
There are, therefore, considerable economic and legal benefits
associated with encryption, the officials said, adding that
restricting the use of encryption could well prevent law-abiding
companies and individuals from protecting themselves against
criminal acts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
