<HEADLINE> Greenspan: US Economy Still Threatened by Inflation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 8 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Federal Reserve (Fed)
Chairman Alan Greenspan warned today that the current economic
expansion could be cut short if inflationary pressures emerge.
</P>
<P>
Greenspan told the U.S. House Budget Committee that inflation
remained the greatest threat to the current expansion which is now
in its seventh year and the third longest on record.
</P>
<P>
In a prepared speech, he said that the strong increases in
employment, which have pushed the U.S. jobless rate down to the
lowest levels in nearly a quarter of a century, may not last. It
may be only a matter of time until tight labor markets trigger
inflation, he added.
</P>
<P>
"The law of supply and demand has not been repealed. If labor
demand continues to outpace sustainable increases in supply, the
question is surely when, not whether, labor costs will escalate
more rapidly," he said.
</P>
<P>
"A re-emergence of inflation is, without question, the greatest
threat to sustaining what has been a balanced economic expansion
virtually without parallel in recent decades," Greenspan stressed.
</P>
<P>
Greenspan also urged the U.S. Congress to aim for budget
surpluses to help cushion the impact of an economic slowdown.
</P>
<P>
He cautioned against putting too much faith in views that rapid
increases in technology had spurred huge gains in productivity and
meant that the economy could grow much faster than previously
believed without generating inflation.
</P>
<P>
Greenspan told the House Budget Committee that it would be
prudent to aim for budget surpluses rather than just a balanced
budget in 2002.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Fed passed up the chances to raise interest rates
since March 25 when it increased the federal fund rate for
short-term bank lending by 1 quarter percentage point. However,
many U.S. economists believe the Fed will be forced to boost rates
to slow economic growth before the end of the year or in early
next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
