<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgium Cuts Budget Deficit as Move Toward Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Belgium has cut 0.5 percentage
points on its 1998 budget in a decisive move toward the single
currency Euro due to be launched in January 1999.
</P>
<P>
The center-left government presented Tuesday its budget for
fiscal 1998 to the parliament, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Belgian Prime Minister Jean-Luc Dehaene told parliamentarians
in his annual budget speech that Belgium is sure to join the
Economic and Monetary Union (EMU).
</P>
<P>
As the most deeply in-debt country among the 15 European Union
member countries, Belgium would cut budget deficit to 2.3 percent
of gross domestic product (GDP) next year from 2.8 percent
currently, Dehaene said.
</P>
<P>
Hardest hit by the budget slash of 17 billion Belgian francs
(469.3 million U.S. dollars) would be the country's pharmaceutical
industry as drug prices and dispensing fees will be curbed.
</P>
<P>
Under the EU Maastricht Treaty, the country's budget deficit
should be at or below 3 percent of its GDP to join the Euro.
</P>
<P>
Yet another Maastricht criteria caught Belgium off-balance.
The treaty required an eligible country should have its debt at no
more than 60 percent of GDP or approaching that level at a
satisfactory pace.
</P>
<P>
Belgium, however, now has a debt up to 125.1 percent of its
GDP, though the new budget plans to reduce it to 122.3 percent of
GDP.
</P>
<P>
The Belgian government said that its budget targets had been
based on conservative forecasts for a 2.5-percent annual economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
The reduction of Belgium's budget deficit has been the result
of more than a decade of revenue raising that has allowed the
government to avoid major new belt-tightening measures as the
country seeks to qualify early for the EMU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
