<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mulroney to Get 2-Mln Dlr Pay in Airbus Affair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Former Canadian Prime Minister
Brian Mulroney will get more than 2 million dollars (1.4 million
US dollars) from the present government to cover his legal
expenses in the Airbus affair, an arbitrator has ruled.
</P>
<P>
The ruling represents the last chapter in the landmark libel
suit between Mulroney and the federal government led by Prime
Minister Jean Chretien.
</P>
<P>
Mulroney sued over the way he was named in a letter to the
Swiss government requesting help in an investigation by the Royal
Canadian Mounted Police (RCMP).
</P>
<P>
He was alleged, among other things, to have received millions
of dollars in illegal commissions in return for helping the sale
of 34 Airbus jets to Air Canada in 1988.
</P>
<P>
The case was settled out of court in January, and the RCMP
began making payments to Mulroney before the arbitration process
had determined the final amount.
</P>
<P>
The RCMP must pay Mulroney 2,006,508 dollars, the federal
police said in a statement Tuesday night. The amount of interest
has not been determined.
</P>
<P>
The figure announced Tuesday means that the case will cost
Canadian taxpayers more than 3.4 million dollars, reports said
today.
</P>
<P>
The announcement could reawaken the criticism the present
government faced at the time of the court case, the reports noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
