<DOCNO> XIE19971009.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Proposes New Air Quality Values </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Asthma sufferers and
environmentalists in Europe today had a good tiding when the
European Commission decided to set new limit values for ambient
air quality.
</P>
<P>
Sulphur dioxide, nitrogen dioxide, particulate matter and lead
are expected to be reduced from 10 percent to 50 percent as
health-based limit values for sulphur dioxide, lead and
particulate matter or dust will be met by 2005.
</P>
<P>
Health-based limit values for nitrogen dioxide and a tighter
set of limit values for dust will be met by 2010.
</P>
<P>
The major goal of the new set of limit values, based on the
revised air quality guidelines for Europe adopted by the World
Health Organization in 1996, is claimed by commission officials as
to provide a high level of protection for public health.
</P>
<P>
To meet the targets, emissions of sulphur dioxide and nitrogen
dioxide from tailpipes of cars and from industrial plants have to
be reduced by big margins.
</P>
<P>
Some industrialists fear that the sharp reduction of emissions
will inevitably entail heavy cost on the part of both car
manufacturers, car fuel producers and consumers.
</P>
<P>
European cities have undergone several episodes of bad air
pollution during the past summer.
</P>
<P>
Paris authorities had to halve the traffic in and out of the
municipality to alleviate the pollution.
</P>
<P>
The main effects of both sulphur dioxide and nitrogen dioxide
are on the respiratory function of human beings while dust is
found to be related to more asthma attacks and higher rates of
death from respiratory and cardiac diseases.
</P>
<P>
The most significant effect of ambient lead on health is
reduced IQ in children and an increase of neo-natal mortality due
to maternal exposure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
