<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Scrutinizes Formula One Television Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission has
confirmed that its competition officials have been scrutinizing the
25-year television broadcast deal by Formula One Holdings (FOH),
report said today.
</P>
<P>
Competition commissioner Karel van Miert made it clear that he
considers extremely long exclusive broadcasting contracts basically
anti-competitive.
</P>
<P>
The FOH is likely to be conferred with the 25-year exclusive
television rights by the International Automobile Federation, the
motor sport's worldwide governing body.
</P>
<P>
Yet FOH legal advisers reportedly believed that FOH's commitment to
maintaining unencrypted TV broadcasts of Formula One Grand Prix races
will be enough to fend off objections on competition grounds.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the executive body of the 15-nation
European Union, received notification of the arrangement of the
deal under Article 85 of the EU Treaty which governs potentially
anti-competitive business pacts.
</P>
<P>
Bernie Ecclestone, Britain's international Grand Prix motor
racing guru, set up the FOH as the vehicle to bring the sport to
the world's television screens.
</P>
<P>
Ecclestone said that he would not go ahead with his planned
flotation of FOH on the stock markets until he has secured an
official exemption from normal EU competition rules. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
