<HEADLINE> David Andrews Appointed New Irish Foreign Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Irish Prime Minister Berti Ahern
has appointed David Andrews as the country's new foreign minister
after former Foreign Minister Ray Burke resigned from parliament
Tuesday amid allegations.
</P>
<P>
Andrews, 61, will take over the co-chairmanship of the Northern
Ireland peace talks, which are aimed at finding a long-lasting
solution to the 28-year-old conflict in the region, according to
reports from Dublin.
</P>
<P>
Andrews, who served as foreign minister from 1992 to 1993, has
been defense minister of the new Irish government since July.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Junior Defense Minister Michael Smith will replace
Andrews as the new defense minister.
</P>
<P>
Burke, who has been accused of accepting a 30,000 Irish punt
(about 43,700 U.S. dollar) political donation from an Irish
businessman in 1989, tendered his resignation following fresh
controversy over the granting of passports to an Arab banker in
1990. 
</P>
