<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Urges Efforts on Water-related Disasters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Department of
Humanitarian Affairs said today that it is time to focus on
socioeconomic impact of floods and drought and to prevent such
disasters.
</P>
<P>
The water-related disasters are affecting more people and
causing more damage than any other disasters, said the
Geneva-based DHA in a press release marking World Disaster
Reduction Day which falls on October, 8.
</P>
<P>
Desertification affects one fourth of the earth's land, and
costs 42 billion U.S. dollars each year in lost productivity,
according to the United Nations Development Program's 1996 Human
Development Report.
</P>
<P>
Poor land management practices are a major contributor,
including overgrazing (grazing areas account for 90 percent of
desertified lands), deforestation, overcultivation (leading to
erosion) and poor irrigation drainage.
</P>
<P>
While drought is the leading killer, with nearly 74,000
reported deaths in 1996, floods are the most frequent and cause
most economic losses.
</P>
<P>
Few countries are spared from floods, not even those in desert
areas. Even in Africa, where drought is the most frequent
disaster, floods and high-wind disasters rank second.
</P>
<P>
Floods in central, southern and northern parts of China from
late June to mid-August in 1996 took 2,700 lives and cost overall
losses of 26.5 billion U.S. dollars with 1.1 million houses
destroyed and 9.1 million damaged, according to the latest Munich
Reinsurance report on "Flooding and Insurance". This is the worst
flooding in the country in 150 years.
</P>
<P>
Many natural disasters are the result of unsolved development
problems, DHA points out. Development patterns that ignore
sustainable water management are exposing communities to greater
risks of floods and drought.
</P>
<P>
While floods between 1991 and 1995 caused nearly 203 billion US
dollars in losses, available water resources are declining at same
time when demand is rising.
</P>
<P>
Although much of the earth's surface is covered by water, DHA
explains, 97.5 percent is salt water, with little potential for
human use. The remaining 2.5 percent of fresh water supply is
mostly locked in polar icecaps, glaciers or groundwaters deep
under the earth.
</P>
<P>
Only a fraction of the world's freshwater supply, 0.26 percent,
is readily accessible from lakes, reservoirs and rivers. Yet even
from that amount, only one third can be harnessed for human needs.
</P>
<P>
World Disaster Reduction Day was launched by the U.N. General
Assembly in 1989, as part of the resolution creating the
International Decade for Natural Disaster Reduction (1990-2000).
</P>
<P>
In a year in which the U.N. has chosen to assess the world's
water resources, the 1997 World Disaster Reduction Campaign
focuses on the need to build a "culture of prevention" to protect
these resources from disasters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971009.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
