<HEADLINE> France, Germany to Sign Police, Customs Convention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 8 (Xinhua) -- French Interior Minister
Jean-Pierre Chevenement and German State Secretary for Interior
Affairs Kurt Schelter will sign Thursday a Franco-German
convention of police and customs cooperation, French officials
said today.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, negotiated between Paris and Bonn for more than
one year within the framework of the Schegen agreements, will be
signed at a meeting of justice and interior ministers of European
Union countries to be held in Mondorf, Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, French and German police and customs
officials will carry out cooperation along three frontier areas
between France and Germany -- Baden-Wurtemberg, Sarre and
Rhenania-Palatinat.
</P>
<P>
French and German police and customs officials will carry out
common control operations 20 kilometers inside the territory of
France and in a definite border area of Germany.
</P>
<P>
France and Germany will also establish in Strasbourg the first
common center of police and customs cooperation between the two
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
