<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FAO's TV Program to Help the Hungry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Food and Agricultural Organization
(FAO) of the United Nations will put a TV and radio program on the
air this year to mobilize awareness and money in the struggle
against hunger, its Near East Regional Office said today.
</P>
<P>
An 11-hour TV and radio program shedding light on poverty,
malnutrition and hunger in the poorest areas in the world will be
broadcast to more than 50 countries by satellite from Rome, FAO's
headquarters, from 14:00 GMT on October 19 to 01:00 GMT the
following day.
</P>
<P>
"It will be the first global telecast dedicated to mobilizing
awareness, solidarity and resources for a campaign to eradicate
hunger," FAO's regional information officer Michael Hage told a
press conference at the FAO's Cairo-based Near East Office here.
</P>
<P>
The idea of Telefood, a global telecast, is FAO's latest drive
to relieve the world's poorest countries of their acute food
shortage, said Hage.
</P>
<P>
Spurred by the political commitment pledged by world leaders at
the World Food Summit in November 1996, FAO has decided to appeal
for financial contributions from countries, businesses and
individuals to support a practical action program.
</P>
<P>
All donations will go directly to FAO's Special Program for
Food Security, which helps poor farmers produce more food by
implementing such improvements as small-scale irrigation and
drainage.
</P>
<P>
The funds, to be collected through locally accredited banks,
will also be available for "grassroots" projects aimed at
assisting the rural poor in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
No funds will be diverted to administrative or other costs and
all contributions will go to providing practical support to the
people benefiting from the Special Program and grassroots projects.
</P>
<P>
Telefood will coincide with the celebrations of the World Food
Day on October 16, with the aim of heightening public awareness of
the problem of world hunger and focusing attention on agriculture
and food production.
</P>
<P>
It also comes when external assistance to developing countries'
agriculture by international donors fell sharply in recent years,
said Hage.
</P>
<P>
International assistance to agriculture in developing countries
fell to around 10 billion U.S. dollars in 1995 from nearly 16
billion dollars in 1988.
</P>
<P>
During the 1996 World Food Summit, participants from 186
countries pledged to reduce the number of undernourished people in
developing countries that tops 800 million.
</P>
<P>
FAO experts attending today's press conference pointed out that
one of the biggest challenges facing humanity is to feed a world
population expected to swell from 5.8 billion in 1997 to 9.4
billion by the year 2050. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
