<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World's First Skin Grown From Human Cells Launched </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The world's first replacement
skin to be grown from human cells was launched by British and
American scientists Tuesday, The Daily Telegraph reported.
</P>
<P>
The dermis named Dermagraft is made by seeding very thin
scaffolds of a polymer with the type of cells called fibroblasts.
The cells grow across the mesh. The polymer scaffolds, made from
the material used for suturing, eventually break down and
disappear.
</P>
<P>
Dr Gail Naughton, the co-inventor of Dermagraft and president
of Advanced Tissue Sciences in California, said in London they
incubated the cells in a medium similar to the environment in the
womb which gave them maximum potential for growth.
</P>
<P>
She said, "The breakthrough has been to understand what cells
do during the normal growth process. That enabled us to simulate
the conditions you would see in a normal growing child. Having
learned how to keep cells happy, the trick was to mimic the body's
environment in the laboratory."
</P>
<P>
Dermagraft is the first product in the range of fully human
engineered tissues. It has been designed to heal foot ulcers in
diabetic patients which are hard to treat. It was launched by
British Smith and Nephew and the US firm.
</P>
<P>
But as the scaffold can be made in any shape or size, other
parts of the body can also be made using the appropriate cells.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971009.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Power Shortage to Worsen in Angola's Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The power supply in the Angolan
capital will worsen as two sub-stations of Cambambe Hydropower
Station which supply power to Luanda will be maintained.
</P>
<P>
Joao Armando, a spokeman for the Luanda Power Supply Company,
told reporters that the power supply will soon be reduced to 50
percent of the demand in Luanda.
</P>
<P>
The generating capacity of Cambambe Hydropower has apparently
dropped because the severe shortage of rain and its power supply
to Luanda has reduced to 60 percent of its normal level, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Shortage of power supply is an problem of long standing in the
Angolan capital mainly because of outdated equipment and damage
of war. 
</P>
