<HEADLINE> Elf Considers Cooperation With China Fundamental </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The French oil group Elf-Aquitaine
considers its cooperation with China and other Asian countries
"fundamental" for its future development, said Philippe Jaffre,
president of Elf-Aquitaine.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with Paris-based Chinese journalists today at
the Elf headquarters in Paris, Jaffre said that as a global
reaching enterprise and with a 1 billion dollar investment plan in
China, Elf wishes to fully establish itself in the Chinese market,
which has a huge potential in the development of oil, chemical and
health products.
</P>
<P>
He said that the forthcoming World Oil Conference to be held in
Beijing will be a very important meeting, which will exert a big
influence over development of oil exploration technologies and
coordination among world oil groups in marketing strategies.
</P>
<P>
Jean Alliot, director of evaluation and programs of Elf, said
that Elf plans to continue its programs of exploration of oil
resources in China, and is now exploring the Tarim basin in
Xinjiang Autonomous Region of China.
</P>
<P>
When Chinese Premier Li Peng visited France in April 1996, Elf
and the Chinese group Sinochem renewed a crude oil supply contract
which covers 1 million tons of crude oil over a two-year period.
</P>
<P>
Elf has signed two contracts with China to market its liquid
petroleum gas (LPG) in Xiamen and Haiyang, and a third is
currently under negotiation.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government also approved in August 1986 the
construction by Elf of a 40,000-ton marine and non-marine
lubricants blending unit in Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
Eric Painvin, director of Elf Oil Asia, Refinery and
Distribution, said that Elf is opening its first chain of oil
service stations in Henan Province of China, and plans to expand
its oil products marketing joint-ventures in China.
</P>
<P>
Elf's wholly-owned subsidiary, Elf Atochem, is investing 300
million U.S. dollars in 14 chemical projects in China, five of
which are already beginning to operate.
</P>
<P>
Elf is now running a dozen ventures in China, including the
Sanofi-Mingsheng Pharmaceuticals company in Hangzhou, the Decco
Agrochemicals company in Kunming, LPG-Haiyang oil refinery company
in Shandong, a hydrogen peroxide company in Shanghai, a
benzylchloride company in Wuhan, a petroleum products company in
Zhengzhou, a plastic additives company in Beijing, a lubricants
company in Guangzhou, and a plating company in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, more than 40 projects have been established between
Elf and Chinese authorities or are under consideration, which is
expected to multiply Elf's sale in China by five times between now
and the year 2,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
