<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Government Warned of "2000 Crisis" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Canada's crucial public services
could be severely disrupted in 2000 unless the government takes
"urgent and aggressive action" to update its computer systems,
warned a report published today.
</P>
<P>
The computer repair task will cost the government at least 1
billion dollars (720 million US dollars), according to the 1997
report of the country's auditor-general.
</P>
<P>
If the task isn't completed on time, the computer systems could
fail when the new millennium falls, crippling vital services such
as search and rescue, commercial cargo clearance and unemployment
insurance payments.
</P>
<P>
At present, most computer software uses two digits, rather than
four, to denote years. The two-digit year in many computers rolls
over to "00" from "99."
</P>
<P>
Without expensive re-writing of software code, computer systems
aren't able to tell the difference between the year 2000 and 1900,
leaving them functioning erratically, it they work at all.
</P>
<P>
The so-called "2000 year crisis" has become a hugely
expensively problem for both the private and public sectors as the
2000 year approaches.
</P>
<P>
The report said now it may be too late for the government to
prepare all of its computer systems in time, which means it may
have to accept that less-important computer functions will
malfunction.
</P>
<P>
By late April, only one-third of the 50 government departments
it surveyed had finished laying out their plans for dealing with
the problem.
</P>
<P>
And only one department was able to show that it had begun
rewriting computer code, the report noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971009.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hussein: Israel Promises No More Attack in Jordan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian King Hussein said here
today that Israel has promised him of carrying no more violent
attacks in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a public rally, Hussein said he has secured promise
from Israel that the intelligence department of the Jewish state
would never conduct any violent actions again in the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that the pledge was made by the Israeli side during
a secret visit to Jordan by Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu, Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai and National
Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon on September 29, four days
after Israeli agents' failed attack on Hamas leader Khaled
Mashaal in Amman.
</P>
<P>
During the visit aimed at solving the crisis, the Israeli
officials met Jordanian Crown Prince Hassan. Netanyahu has
expressed regret over the assassination attempt by two Israeli
Mossad agents and apologized to Jordan officially, Hussein said.
</P>
<P>
He said that after the attack, he received letters from
inside Jordan, the Arab and Islamic world, Israeli personalities
and Jews worldwide denouncing the bungled attack on the Hamas
leader.
</P>
<P>
Before the king made the speech this afternoon, Hamas released
a statement, saying that it did not want to open dialogue with
Israel and it did not send any message to Israel for opening
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
However, Hussein said that two days before the attack, he sent
a letter to Netanyahu, telling him that there is a possibility for
a dialogue between Hamas and Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian-Israeli relations, which went strained by the
attack on Mashaal, were becoming normal after Israel began to
release Jordanian and Palestinian detainees and pledged to abide
by all the provisions in the peace treaty it signed with Jordan,
Jordanian Minister of State for Information Affairs Samir Mutawe
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Under a Hussein-brokered bargain after the failed attack, Israel
released long-jailed ailing Sheikh Ahmed Yassin, founder of
Hamas, on October 1 and allowed him to return to his home in Gaza
in exchange for the release of the two Israeli Mossad agents who
attacked Mashaal.
</P>
<P>
Hamas was established in 1987 to fight against Israel`s
occupation of Palestine. Most of its political bureau members
live in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Jordan signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994 and is one of
the two Arab countries that conceived peace with the Jewish
state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
