<HEADLINE> Canada's Wheat Production to Drop Below 5-Year Average </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Canada's wheat production is
expected to drop 20.8 percent to 23.6 million tons this year due
to reduced planted acreage and lower yields.
</P>
<P>
Statistics Canada said today in its September production
estimates that of all the major crops surveyed, only canola,
soybeans and flaxseed were reported to show an increase in
production.
</P>
<P>
"Total wheat production has been adversely affected by both a
reduction of 2.4 million seeded acres this year and a yield
decrease of 5 bushels per acre," the federal statistics agency
said.
</P>
<P>
"Production will drop by 6.2 million tons this year -- 3.4
million tons below the five-year average," the agency noted.
</P>
<P>
Average yield for spring wheat in the Prairie provinces
declined by more than 5 bushels per acre.
</P>
<P>
Durum yield in Manitoba province dropped 11 bushels per acre
from last year, the lowest since 1989.
</P>
<P>
Though climatic conditions in Ontario province were more
favorable for wheat, reduced harvested area will lower production.
</P>
<P>
As for barley, production will fall by about 2.0 million tons
compared with last year. This represents the largest drop in
production since 1988.
</P>
<P>
Canola production in the country is expected to reach 6.1
million tons this year, up 19.6 percent than last year.
</P>
<P>
Soybean production will hit a record 2.7 million tons, up
22.7 percent than in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
