<HEADLINE> Lack of Seamen Complained at Maritime Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The shortage of qualified
seafaring personnel is one of the key problems facing the world's
shipping industry, an international shipping conference was told.
</P>
<P>
The interest of young people for a career at sea is
diminishing, said Vassos Pyrgos, Permanent Secretary of the Cyprus
Communications and Works Ministry, here today. But he did not give
detailed description of the situation.
</P>
<P>
He was making the complaints at the closing session of the
three-day Maritime Cyprus 1997 conference which was attended by
1,000 delegates from over 30 countries.
</P>
<P>
These problems, plus a general lack of welfare facilities and
uncertain social benefits, result in high labor costs, lower
quality, higher morbidity and labor unrest, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, Pyrgos said the good news is that international
instruments have been put in place to regulate the training,
working and living conditions, the social benefits and the welfare
of the seafarers.
</P>
<P>
Pyrgos urged all involved in the shipping industry, maritime
administrations, ship-owners, underwriters, port authorities and
seamen's organizations to combine their efforts to overcome the
existing problems.
</P>
<P>
He said the conference, which focused on the existing problems
in the industry, proved to be a "significant source of
information."
</P>
<P>
It provided "feedback and advice on the basis of which to
develop, review and adapt our maritime policy and direct our
actions," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
