<HEADLINE> Canadians Eat More Vegetables, Fruits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Canadians have increased their
consumption of vegetables by almost a quarter over the past two
decades, Statistics Canada said today.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, each Canadian ate almost 180 kilograms of vegetables,
up 22 percent from 147 kilograms 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Potatoes, the traditional favorite, led the way as consumption
reached almost 70 kilograms per person last year.
</P>
<P>
And lettuce, carrots, onions, tomatoes and cabbage also
remained popular with Canadian consumers.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, total fruit consumption in Canada reached just over
120 kilograms per person, up 17 percent from the mid-1970s.
</P>
<P>
Bananas topped the list at over 13 kilograms per person,
followed by apples and oranges.
</P>
<P>
Canadians were also including more fish and shellfish products
in their diet, although red meat and poultry remained the most
popular choices for many consumers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
