<HEADLINE> Zambia to Import $37M Worth of Maize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lusaka, October 8 (Xinhua) -- A senior Zambian official said
here today that the government intends to import 37 million U.S.
Dollars worth of maize to fill the demand gap caused by reduction
of output.
</P>
<P>
The Zambia News Agency quoted Ackson Sejani, Deputy Minister
of Agriculture, Good and Fisheries as saying in parliament that
the government intends to import about five million bags (90 kg
each) of maize to meet the shortfall from the expected output of
10 million bags of maize during the 1996-1997 agricultural
season.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that much of the maize imports will come from
north and south America.
</P>
<P>
Zambia, where maize is a staple for the people, is expected to
produce 10 million bags of maize but recorded a deficiency of
five million bags, according to Sejani.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, Edith Nawakwi, minister of the same
ministry, stressed that last season's floods and other factors
affected the whole Southern Africa Development Community (SADC)
region which has recorded a shortfall of 60 million bags in maize
production.
</P>
<P>
In view of the shortfall and the impending drought as a result
of the El Nino phenomenon during the coming season, Nawakwi said
the Zambian government has been compelled to import maize through
the food reserve agency and in connection with the private sector
and donors. 
</P>
