<DOCNO> XIE19971009.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Considers Assisting Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) announced today it will provide a financial rescue
package to Indonesia in the wake of a sharp fall in the value of
its currency.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to voice his support for Indonesia's economic
program, Michel Camdessus, the IMF managing director, expressed
his welcome to the Indonesian government's measures to respond to
the recent pressure in the foreign exchange market.
</P>
<P>
"Over the last few months the IMF has been working closely with
the Indonesian authorities in developing an adequate response to
the crisis in Southeast Asia," Camdessus said. "The IMF strongly
supports the approach that has been followed by Indonesia, which
sees this as an occasion to strengthen its economic policies even
if fundamentals are basically sound," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The IMF chief said it would send a team of experts to Jakarta
this week to work out details and would cooperate closely with
World Bank and Asian Development Bank teams already in the field.
</P>
<P>
The move was the latest by these international organizations to
help financially troubled Asian economies. The IMF and a group of
countries led by Japan provided Thailand with 17 billion U.S.
dollars in August, the second biggest rescue package after 50
billion dollars for Mexico in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The IMF also put together an aid package for the Philippines
early in the summer.
</P>
<P>
"Two IMF teams will arrive in Jakarta this week to begin
discussions on an IMF-supported economic program and to provide
technical assistance on financial sector reform," said Camdessus.
</P>
<P>
The value of Indonesia's currency, the rupiah, has lost 18.6
percent in the last two weeks, partly because of Thailand's
crisis. Since the beginning of the year it has lost 40 percent of
its value. 
</P>
</TEXT>
