<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa has hailed Uganda's Makerere University for the
role it played in developing Uganda, east Africa and the
sub-Sahara region in general.
</P>
<P>
He made the statement today while giving a speech at the
university on its contribution to national and international
development to mark the 75th anniversary of the university.
</P>
<P>
The university, well known far and near in east Africa, has
trained and turned out many leaders and public servants during
the transition period from colonial administration to independent
government.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa also praised the university for opening its door without
discrimination to all those who are qualified.
</P>
<P>
He contributed 10 million Shillings (about ten thousand U.S.
Dollars) to the university which is his Alma Mater for the
expansion of its library.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
briefed Mkapa on plans to expand the university and other Ugandan
institutions of higher learning to ensure that higher education
is accessible to all people in the country.
</P>
<P>
While the university could only admit 5,000 students in 1986,
Museveni said, it now caters for 15,000 and will be expanded to
enroll up to 20,000 in future. 
</P>
