<HEADLINE> Mubarak Blames CIA for Libyan Dissident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
today denied Cairo was involved in the disappearance of a
prominent Libyan dissident in Cairo and put the blame on the
U.S. Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) instead.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters at the Suez Canal city of Ismailia today,
Mubarak dismissed as "random and baseless accusations" that Egypt
abducted Libyan dissident Mansour Kekhia in Cairo and then handed
him over to the Libyan government.
</P>
<P>
A CIA report, quoted by the Washington Post on September 28,
said Egyptian agents staged the 1993 abduction. The alleged
kidnaping is reportedly causing tension between Cairo and
Washington.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak suggested that the Jewish lobby in the United States
was behind the CIA report so as to avenge Israel's failure to get
back a convicted spy from Egyptian prison.
</P>
<P>
"The subject resurfaced because of Azzam Azzam," he said,
referring to the Israeli spy recently sentenced to 15 years in
prison on charges of spying on Egypt for Israel.
</P>
<P>
Kekhia had served as Libyan foreign minister and ambassador to
the U.N. before defecting to the U.S. in 1980. He vanished from
the Safir Hotel in Dokki, west Cairo, on December 11, 1993.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said he feared that the CIA had got Kekhia out of Egypt.
</P>
<P>
"If there is fresh evidence on the subject, the public
prosecution in Egypt is ready to look into it," the president
said. But he added that it should be "of our own will and not as a
result of any pressure."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has long accused Libya of sponsoring global
terrorism. But Egypt is making efforts to have the United Nations
Security Council ease sanctions imposed on Libya since 1992.
</P>
</TEXT>
