<HEADLINE> Clinton Wishes Erez Summit Will Get Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 8 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton hoped
today that a meeting between Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu could put back on track
the peace process in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
"The fact that they met is encouraging," Clinton told reporters
at the White House. "The most important thing is that it occurred
and it occurred not a moment too soon."
</P>
<P>
Arafat and Netanyahu met in the early hours today at Erez, the
Gaza Strip. It was their first meeting in eight months after the
peace process was disrupted by Jewish settlement building in March
which soon led to violent clashes between Palestinian protesters
and Israeli police and finally to two bombing incidents in
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the turmoil of the last week, including a botched
Israeli assassination attempt on a Hamas leader, had created
conditions for the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"It may be that the developments of the last few days have been
so troubling and so difficult that it has gotten the attention of
both sides and clarified the necessity for them to get back to
talking with each other and to get this peace process back on
track, I hope," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton noted U.S. Middle East mediator Dennis Ross had played
an important role in arranging the summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
"I am pleased Ambassador Ross was able to put it together," he
said. But he stressed at the same time that it was up to Arafat
and Netanyahu to "characterize the nature and results of the
discussions they had."
</P>
<P>
Ross, speaking in Ramallah, the West Bank, said today that he
believed the summit meeting at Erez marked a new beginning.
</P>
<P>
"We had a very good meeting last night that I think does mark a
new beginning and it's especially important because the leaders
committed themselves to overcome all the differences," Ross said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton met Israeli President Ezer Weizman in Washington
Tuesday and suggested the series of tragic events in the region
over the last several months might provide the impetus to revive
the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
