<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Hiring More Welfare Recipients </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 8 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said today that his administration has witnessed the largest
decline ever in the country's welfare rolls, a drop of 3.6
million.
</P>
<P>
Clinton described it as "yet another piece of evidence that
welfare reform is working far better than anyone had predicted it
would." The decline also has been attributed to the nation's
strong economy.
</P>
<P>
He said that in the first 10 months of the new law, through
June 1997, welfare rolls declined by 1.7 million to just under
10.5 million. For the first time since 1969, less than four
percent of the U.S. population is on welfare.
</P>
<P>
Clinton called on businesses to take advantage of available tax
credits to hire workers off the welfare rolls. 
