<HEADLINE> IDB Approves Loan for Health Program in Dominican Republic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American
Development Bank (IDB) today announced the approval of a 61.2
million U.S. dollar loan to the Dominican Republic for the first
phase of its health improvement program.
</P>
<P>
The resources will finance investments in technical assistance,
training, service provision, infrastructure and equipment that
will support institutional and service delivery reforms to improve
health care for low- and middle-income citizens.
</P>
<P>
The social insurance-financed health system will be modernized,
separating the pension, accident, and health funds and
establishing a system in which insured families select a provider
network among a menu of competing networks.
</P>
<P>
Besides, four public hospitals will be upgraded and become
autonomously governed, model facilities employing modern
management tools and technologies.
</P>
<P>
Two pilot projects will be financed to provide basic health
service, including insurance, to low-income groups.
</P>
<P>
Co-financing for the IDB program is being offered by the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries with 5 million
dollars and the Nordic Development Fund, with 3.5 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The program is designed to help carry out the first five years
of health reform expected to take between eight to 12 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
