<HEADLINE> Lack of Facilities Affects Ghanaian Varsities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Nearly two-thirds of candidates
in Ghana who qualified for entry into universities now cannot get
in because of inadequate accommodation and teaching facilities.
</P>
<P>
For some universities, they each could only accept about 1,400
fresh men and women while more than 5,000 are actually qualified,
the British Broadcasting Corporation reported today.
</P>
<P>
The situation has been getting worse each year with the growth
of the population, it said.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, everyone agrees that more
universities should be established or existing facilities
expanded, but hardly anyone seems to have a clue as to how to
finance them.
</P>
<P>
The government policy has been to spend comparatively more on
primary education in order to achieve good quality, nearly free
basic education for all children and for parents to share the
cost of secondary and higher education.
</P>
<P>
But the National Union of Ghana students say their parents are
broke and cannot afford it.
</P>
<P>
Not everyone believes that, saying that hundreds of students
are travelling to Europe and America during their holidays while
enjoying music from hifi equipment in their home.
</P>
<P>
Ghana's education minister was quoted as arguing that many
parents spent much more to send their children to private primary
schools than they were being asked to pay at universities.
</P>
<P>
In many cases, the government expects that secondary school
graduates who are able to enter university to pursue vocational
and technical careers.
</P>
<P>
But that's not an appealing option especially for those who
have made the university entry grades. They don't want to settle
for mercenary when they can be architects or for book-keeping
when they can be fund managers.
</P>
<P>
Critics of the educational system are particularly upset
because of reports that several ministers and presidents have
sent their children to universities overseas.
</P>
<P>
They say it demonstrates a lack of faith in the government's
own education system, while government counterargue that their
children have a right to be educated anywhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
The report predicted the fund problem would become the number
one question for Ghana's university entrance examination next
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
