<HEADLINE> Israeli-Palestinian Washington Talks Postponed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 8 (Xinhua) -- an originally scheduled
Israeli-Palestinian meeting in Washington next week to seek ways
of revitalizing peace process has been postponed as time available
is too short for lengthy discussions, the State Department said on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin told reporters that the
U.S.-sponsored talks between Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy
and Mahmoud Abbas, a senior advisor to Yasser Arafat, would have
had only two day to meet because the major Jewish holiday Succot
begins at sundown next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
And a summit meeting between Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu and Palestinian leader Arafat at Erez, Gaza Strip,
earlier Wednesday also gave boost to "shake up" the schedule for
the originally planned Washington meeting.
</P>
<P>
"We want to be able to have them (Levy and Abbas) stay longer
than two days," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
The four issues to be discussed between Levy and Abbas are
those of further redeployment of Israeli forces in Palestinian
areas, a time-out in new Jewish settlement construction, ways to
advance to negotiations between the Israelis and Palestinians on
the final "permanent status", and security cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Talks on those issues "will continue at various levels through
our normal channels and then a schedule will be developed for
further discussions," Rubin said. "The focus of attention should
now be on the interim committees" looking at the use of
Palestinian airports and seaports and on safe passage between the
West Bank and the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
The resumption of the interim committees and next week's
Washington talks were agreed during talks in New York between
Israeli and Palestinian officials on September 29. 
</P>
</TEXT>
