<HEADLINE> UN Sanctions Won't Hurt S. Leone: Junta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The military junta in Sierra
Leone said today that sanctions ordered by the United Nations
Security Council would not affect the country.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions would only "hurt the poor" instead of the
military government, said a junta spokesman, quoted by the
British Broadcasting Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council decided earlier today to impose sanctions
on the military junta in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
In a resolution which was unanimously adopted this morning,
the Security Council called on all states to prevent the entry
into or transit through their territories of members of the
military junta and adult members of their families.
</P>
<P>
The council also called on all states to prevent the sale or
supply to Sierra Leone, by their nationals or from their
territories, or using their flag vessels or aircraft, of
petroleum and petroleum products and arms and related materials
of all types, including weapons and ammunition, military vehicles
and equipment, paramilitary equipment and spare parts.
</P>
<P>
The council urged the military junta to immediately hand over
power to the democratically-elected government it overthrew in
the May 25 coup.
</P>
<P>
It reiterated that the military junta must end all acts of
violence and cease all interference with the delivery of
humanitarian assistance to the people of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Similar measures were taken by the Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS) more than a month ago to press the junta
to step down.
</P>
<P>
The economic sanctions and and embargo ordered by ECOWAS has
been enforced by the sub-regional peace-keeping force known as
ECOMOG, which has warned to attack any violator.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council resolution, which ECOWAS has been
seeking, also expressed strong support for the efforts of the
ECOWAS committee of five to resolve the crisis in the country and
encouraged it to continue to work for the peaceful restoration of
constitutional order, including through the resumption of
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The committee is made up of foreign ministers of Nigeria,
Ghana, Cote d'Ivoire, Guinea and Liberia.
</P>
<P>
The council called on all states, international organizations
and financial institutions to assist west African states to
address the economic and social consequences of the influx of
refugees from Sierra Leone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
