<HEADLINE> Somali Factions Agree on Meeting at Arab League </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The main Somali factions today
agreed to meet at the Arab League (AL) headquarters in Cairo this
month in a bid to end the country's seven-year civil war, a senior
AL official said.
</P>
<P>
The upcoming meeting aims to pave the way for a national
reconciliation conference slated for Bosaso, south of Somali
capital of Mogadishu, on November 1, said Samir Hosni, who is in
charge of the Somali file in the AL.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the factions have already accepted the proposal
by AL Secretary General Esmat Abdul Meguid on holding a
preparatory meeting here to narrow their differences regarding the
main issues to be raised in the national reconciliation
conference, Hosni said.
</P>
<P>
There is full coordination between the AL and the Egyptian
Foreign Ministry towards the necessity of helping the Somali
factions to overcome their crisis, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Cairo meeting will be attended by leader of the Somali
Salvation Alliance Ali Mahdi Mohamed and leader of the Somali
Congress Party Hussein Farah Aideed, together with a number of
Somali National Salvation Council leaders.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed and Aideed signed a reconciliation agreement here on
May 29 on holding peaceful talks to end the civil war that has
ravaged the country since 1991. Egypt has been involved in
mediating an end to the Somali crisis in the past few months.
</P>
<P>
The Arab League is currently coordinating efforts with the
U.N. and the Organization of African Unity as well as major
countries in the area such as Egypt and Ethiopia to activate the
Somali reconciliation process.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1991 ouster of the late President Mohamed Siad Barre,
Somalia has been fragmented into fiefdoms protected by faction
leaders, who continued to fight to expand their spheres of
influence despite several unsuccessful peace conferences.
</P>
<P>
The factional fighting, combined with a 1992 famine, has
claimed about 350,000 lives in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
