<HEADLINE> Zambia's Ministry of Agriculture to Cut 2,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- About 2,000 posts will be
reduced by the end of November in Zambia's Ministry of
Agriculture, Food and Fisheries, the official Zambia News Agency
Zana reported today.
</P>
<P>
Zana quoted the ministry's Permanent Secretary Kabeta Muleya
as saying here today that only 4,000 staff will be given jobs by
his ministry after November 30.
</P>
<P>
This is apparently a bold move to promote the efficiency of
the ministry and reduce the red tape, which is a common case in
the administrative departments of the country.
</P>
<P>
At present, the ministry has more than 7,000 employees, all of
whom have applied for the existing 4,900 vacancies, said Muleya.
</P>
<P>
According to him, a committee comprising of non-civil servants
appointed by the country's public service commission has been
conducting interviews and reviewing the experience,
qualifications and the personality of the candidates for the
positions.
</P>
<P>
The composition of the panel is such that the people in the
team have no attachment to the ministry's current staff in case
they swerve the rules and recruit people who are not qualified
for the positions, the secretary noted.
</P>
<P>
There is no overwhelming response from the ministry's
employees, said Muleya, adding it is a pity that many qualified
people will not be accepted because of the limited vacancies.
</P>
<P>
Those who will not be picked by the ministry will be told of
their new status soon and their pensions and other terminal
benefits will be addressed by the cabinet office through civil
service management division, he added.
</P>
<P>
Under zambia's labor law, employees cannot be fired unless
they are compensated with a large sum of "terminal benefits".
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
