<HEADLINE> World Bank to Provide Guarantees for Egyptian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 8 (Xinhua) -- To beef up Egypt's burgeoning
private sector, the World Bank (WB) today announced a new strategy
to shield private investors from any loss from the breach of
contract by the government.
</P>
<P>
Khaled Ikram, director of Egypt Department at the World Bank,
said that the bank will sign written guarantees by which it will
pay back any loss the private sector might incur if the government
backtracks from having it carry out infrastructure ventures.
</P>
<P>
"The bank has taken such decision due to the courageous
economic steps taken by Egypt that helped both sides reach a high
level of confidence," Ikram said on the sidelines of symposium on
the participation of the private sector in infrastructure projects
in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Investments of infrastructure projects in developing countries
reach 250 billion U.S. dollars, 15 percent of which are private
sector investments, according to Nemat Shafiq, head of Private
Sector Development Department at the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
She said Egypt has given the private sector a much free hand by
letting them carry out infrastructure ventures, especially in the
fields of power, airport and harbors.
</P>
<P>
Shafiq pointed out that competition forces the private sector
to improve the quality of the services and enhance their
accessibility to all classes of projects..
</P>
<P>
"When the private sector implements such projects, the state
will receive more taxes and wages of workers will be improved,"
she said, adding that some of them will even be share-holders in
companies.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian government's privatization policy was launched in
1991 but actually took off in 1996.
</P>
<P>
By June 1997, nearly 22 percent of the public sector had been
offered for sale in Egypt, according to official figures.
</P>
<P>
Participation of the private sector represented 60 percent of
the volume of economic activities in Egypt by 1995, a 50 percent
rise over the 1970s. The private sector is expected to shoulder 70
percent of the country's investments in the coming years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971009.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Identifies "Terrorist" Groups </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright on Wednesday identified 30 foreign groups as "terrorist"
organizations, making it illegal to provide funds for them and
denying their members or representatives U.S. visas.
</P>
<P>
In announcing the move mandated by a 1996 U.S. law, Albright
said the goal of the designation was to "make the United States
fully a no-support-for-terrorism zone."
</P>
<P>
The 1996 law was approved following the Oklahoma City bombing
in 1995. That seeks to curb foreign terrorism. But the person
responsible for the bombing turned out to be U.S citizens
</P>
<P>
Upon the announcement, President Bill Clinton said in a
statement during a political trip in New Jersey that "the United
States is committed to fight against those who speak the language
of terror."
</P>
<P>
Two weeks ago, the House, impatient over the slow pace of
identifying the "terrorist groups", voted 396-6, to cut State
Department salaries and expenses by 2 percent until the list was
completed.
</P>
<P>
The foreign groups named as "terrorist" organizations include
the Islamic resistance organization Hamas, the Basque group ETA,
the Hezbollah organization, the Khmer Rouge, the Kurdistan
Workers' party, and Peru's Shining Path and Tupac Amaru
Revolutionary Movement.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin said that although the
IRA was not included in the list, the United States intended to
keep it "under active review." The designations expire in two
years' time unless renewed, but groups could be added to the
list in future, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
