<DOCNO> XIE19971009.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. 1996 Foreign Military Aid Near $9 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government provided
872 million U.S. dollars of military supplies to foreign nations
and regions in 1996 and approved another 270.5 million dollars in
cut-rate sales of used U.S. defense equipment, the Defense News
said in its latest edition.
</P>
<P>
As part of its effort to cultivate global influence, the U.S.
defense aid covered more than 120 countries and regions, spanning
the globe, from Eastern Europe and Bosnia to the Middle East and
Central America, the military weekly said, citing a White House
report to Congress.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East was the biggest recipient with 388.8 million
dollars, followed by Europe, 246 million dollars, and Latin
America, 109.4 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The outright grants to the Middle East mainly went to Egypt,
Jordan and Israel, while Bosnia was the largest recipient of
emergency drawdown equipment.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the Pentagon gave away 495 million
dollars in excess defense articles (EDA), equipment determined no
longer to be needed by U.S. military, including M60A3 tanks, M16
rifles, M113 armored personnel carriers.
</P>
<P>
Also it gave away 338 million dollars worth of equipment
through emergency drawdowns, which was Congressionally mandated
assistance in the form of defense items taken from U.S. military
stocks, and 39 million dollars in International Military
Educational and Training funds.
</P>
<P>
By comparison, the U.S. gave away about 154 million dollars in
EDA in 1994 and about 138 million dollars in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
