<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 15:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli FM Says He Opposes Failed Murder Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Foreign Minister
David Levy said today that if he had known about the failed murder
attack by two Israel agents on a Hamas leader in advance, he would
have opposed it.
</P>
<P>
During an interview with Israel Radio, he said that he would
have made his position clear to Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
if he had known the operation beforehand.
</P>
<P>
Levy refused to comment on the prime minister's role during the
affair or the decision-making process, which led up to the
operation.
</P>
<P>
But he said that if he had been one of the decision-makers
involved in the affair, he would have not let the operation get
off the ground.
</P>
<P>
The failed attack on Hamas leader Khaled Mashaal in Amman late
last month has caused serious damage to Israel, Levy said. He
warned that he will resign if he reaches conclusion that he can no
longer have impact on or improve the government performance.
</P>
<P>
The bungled attack forced Israel to release Hamas founder
Sheikh Ahmed Yassin and allow him to return his home in the Gaza
Strip in exchange for the release of the two agents carrying out
the attack and detained by Jordanian police.
</P>
<P>
After the attack, the Canadian government recalled its
ambassador to Israel to protest over the misuse of Canadian
passports by the two agents.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, former Mossad Director Nahum Admoni resigned today
from the state committee of inquiry, which is in charge of
investigating the Mashaal affair. And his resignation was
approved by the Israeli cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Attorney General Elyakim Rubinstein said that Admoni
had to step down because of his recent statement defending the
failed operation in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister's office announced that it is proposing
former Air Force Commander Dan Tolchovsky to replace Admoni.
</P>
</TEXT>
