<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Sees More Vehicle Sales in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Canada's consumer demand for new
motor vehicles registered a record high in August as more
automobiles were sold than during any other months since the early
1990s.
</P>
<P>
Statistics released today indicate that consumers bought a
total of 120,866 new cars and trucks in August, a 2.8 percent
increase from the previous month and a 21.1 percent rise over the
same month last year.
</P>
<P>
Since mid-1996, sales of new motor vehicles in the country have
generally been on the upswing.
</P>
<P>
Even though the current sales levels are the highest since the
early 1990s, they remain below the levels reached in the late
1980s, the federal statistics agency noted.
</P>
<P>
Between January and August this year, dealers sold 915,941 new
vehicles in all, the highest eight-month total since 1990.
</P>
<P>
The strong sales performance is generally attributed by the
industry to improved consumer confidence, modest job growth and
lower interest rates.
</P>
<P>
In addition, leasing has been a major factor in the sales of
new vehicles, the agency said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
