<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Bamboo Slip Exhibition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- A cache of bamboo and wood
slips dating back 1,700 years were exhibited today in central
China's Hunan Province.
</P>
<P>
Last October, tens of thousands of bamboo and wood slips were
unearthed in downtown Changsha, capital of central China's Hunan
Province.
</P>
<P>
The slips, which are inscribed with over 200,000 characters,
are part of the largest discovery of its kind, and will contribute
greatly to studies of the Three Kingdoms Period (220-280).
</P>
<P>
Archeologists note that the find is as important as the
discovery of the world famous Shang Dynasty (16th-11th Century BC)
oracle bones and shells in central China's Henan Province and the
Dunhuang documents found in the Mogao Grottos in northwest China's
Gansu Province.
</P>
<P>
The slips, which were unearthered from a pit, provide a
detailed record of the political, economic, military, cultural and
geographic situation in Changsha prefecture which was under the
rule of the Wu State (222-280).
</P>
<P>
The records covered tax, rental and birth records. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
