<HEADLINE> China Maintains Stable Retail Prices in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 9 (Xinhua) -- China maintained stable market
prices in September, with the retail price index remaining
unchanged on the previous year's period, but rising by 1.1 percent
on the August level.
</P>
<P>
Statistics released today by the State Planning Commission also
show that that consumer goods price index rose by 1.8 percent on
the same month last year, and was up 1.7 percent from August.
</P>
<P>
The average retail price index during the first nine months of
the year grew by 1.3 percent on the 1996 period. Price hikes in 14
provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions remained below
the national average level. Shanghai, Jiangsu and Anhui enjoyed
negative growth, with Beijing recording the highest level of 4.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
The average retail price index in 36 major cities rose by 1.3
percent for the first nine month, with the retail price index for
September rising by one percentage point on the August figure.
</P>
</TEXT>
