<HEADLINE> PNA Denies Any Criticism of Jordan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) today rejected media reports that President Yasser
Arafat criticized Jordan for its release of two alleged Israeli
agents.
</P>
<P>
PNA Minister of Planning and International Cooperation Nabil
Sha'ath described the reports talking such a criticism as
groundless, Jerusalem Media and Communication Center said.
</P>
<P>
On October 6, Jordan released two alleged Israeli agents for
attempting to kill Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas)'s leader
Khaled Mashaal in Jordan last month.
</P>
<P>
The reports published today quoted Arafat as telling a secret
meeting in Ramallah Wednesday that "there is a conspiracy to
undermine the PNA."
</P>
<P>
He was reported to have accused Jordanian King Hussein for
forming "an alliance with Hamas against the PNA" by freeing
Israeli agents in exchange for Hamas founder Sheikh Ahmed Yassin.
</P>
<P>
Some other reports even said that Arafat in his address had
alluded a plot involving Israel, the United States, Jordan and
Hamas to bypass the PNA to speak for the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
All these reports were groundless and Arafat criticized nobody,
Sha'ath said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Palestinian Cabinet is scheduled to convene its
weekly session in Ramallah Thursday evening to discuss the latest
political developments in light of the recent meeting between
Arafat and Israeli Prime minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Arafat and Netanyahu met on Wednesday morning at Erez
checkpoint between Jerusalem and Gaza, in which the two tried to
find out their differences concerning the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is the first between the two Israeli and
Palestinian leaders since March when the peace process sank in
crisis with the start of Israeli construction of settlement in
Arab East Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
