<HEADLINE> Cambodian PMs Pledge to Hold Elections As Scheduled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian Prime Ministers Ung
Huot and Hun Sen said here today that Cambodia will hold general
elections in May 1998 as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
The elections can proceed as scheduled as long as various
parties make joint efforts, said the two prime ministers when
addressing a press conference held at Phnom Penh's Pochentong
International Airport upon return from their diplomatic trip to
France and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The Cambodian government welcomes exiled political figures
abroad to return home for the scheduled elections next year, said
Ung Huot and Hun Sen.
</P>
<P>
As for whether the ousted First Prime Minister Prince Norodom
Ranariddh can run in the elections, Hun Sen said Ranariddh has the
right to campaign so far, but his future hinges upon the verdict
of court.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh, who has been in exile since he was ousted in July,
was accused by Hun Sen of illegally negotiating with Khmer Rouge
guerrillas and of possible involvement in illegal import of
weapons.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia's draft election law, now in parliamentary committee,
holds that convicted criminals may not stand as candidates.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen also complained about the decision of the United
Nations to leave vacant Cambodia's seat at the 52nd General
Assembly. But he believed this matter, which he said concerns the
role of the U.N. in Cambodia, will be solved soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
