<HEADLINE> Klim Breaks Pankatrov's World Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Michael Klim highlighted the
Australian swimming championships with a world record showing in
Brisbane on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Klim broke Russian Denis Pankratov's 100-meter butterfly world
mark just 20 minutes after a lengthy false start.
</P>
<P>
The 20-year-old splashed home in 52.15 seconds, slicing 0.12
seconds from the previous world standard at the meeting which also
serves as Australia's trials for January's world championships.
</P>
<P>
Klim is the first Australian man to set a world record in the
100 meters butterfly.
</P>
<P>
Klim won a world championship slot 20 minutes after a false
start which saw swimmers complete 65 meters before officials could
stop them.
</P>
<P>
"I think the false start was good psychologically for me
because I'm a tough swimmer," Klim said. "I proved it I guess."
</P>
<P>
Geoff Huegill finished second in 53.16 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Elli Overton won the women's 200 meters individual medley by
touching 2:16.66. Emma Johnson was second in 2:17.24.
</P>
<P>
In the men's 200 meters breaststroke, Simon Cowley came home
first in a time of 2:16.09, followed by Ryan Mitchell in 2:16.30.
</P>
</TEXT>
