<HEADLINE> China's First Red Cross Hospital Celebrates 90th Anniversary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai's Huashan Hospital,
the first hospital opened by the Red Cross Society of China,
celebrated its 90th anniversary today.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin and Premier Li Peng wrote
inscriptions expressing appreciation for the hospital, and Huang
Ju, Member of the Political Bureau of the Central Committee of the
Chinese Communist Party, sent a letter of congratulations.
</P>
<P>
The hospital, founded in 1907, is a comprehensive institution
focusing on medical treatment, education and scientific research.
</P>
<P>
The hospital's departments, including the medical, surgical and
dermatology departments, are equipped with state-of-the-art
equipment and use advanced international techniques. The hospital
treats more than 900,000 emergency cases annually, with some 40
percent of the cases involving transferrals of people suffering
from rare diseases. Huashan has recorded a success rate
approaching 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
The hospital opened Shanghai's first ward for foreigners and
has since treated tens of thousands of patients from 60 countries
and regions. Eight consulates in the city jointly presented an
honorary medal to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
The hospital has participated in poverty relief activities and
provided assistance to people in disaster areas. It has also
lowered medical fees for 166 poor patients by some 1.9 million
yuan (235,000 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Huashan has donated medical apparatus to elderly pensioners.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
