<DOCNO> XIE19971009.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Vows Further Support for Thai Economic Restructuring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto today pledged further financial support to help Thailand
rebuild its ailing economy.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto made the pledge during a 45-minute meeting with his
visiting Thai counterpart Chavalit Yongchaiyudh at his official
residence, Kyodo News quoted government officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Overcoming difficulties for the Thai economy is not something
that involves Thailand alone, and is important for recovering
trust in the whole economy of Southeast Asia," Hashimoto was
quoted as telling Chavalit.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto asked Thailand to steadily implement its economic
rehabilitation package and work out measures which can gain the
confidence of the market and steadfastly carry them out, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
In a response, Chavalit said that Thailand will comply with
agreements in the International Monetary Fund (IMF) package
although they are difficult for the country, according to the
officials.
</P>
<P>
Japan offered two new types of trade insurance, which were
worth 1 billion U.S. dollars in total, over two years to increase
funds supply of the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Japan contributed 4 billion dollars in loans to a 17.2 billion
dollar package devised recently by the IMF to rescue Thailand from
its economic crisis, which stemmed from the plunge of the baht
against the dollar in July.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Chavalit, who arrived here Wednesday on a
three-day visit, promised to improve his country's investment
environment to attract more Japanese investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
