<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Dramatist Wins 1997 Nobel Literature Prize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The 1997 Nobel prize for
literature goes to Italian dramatist and actor Dario Fo, the
Swedish Academy announced here today.
</P>
<P>
As one of the leading figures in modern farce and political
drama, Dario Fo "emulates the jesters of the Middle Ages in
scourging authority and upholding the dignity of the downtrodden,"
said the Academy.
</P>
<P>
Fo has been performed for many years all over the world and his
influence keeps increasing.
</P>
<P>
"With a blend of laughter and gravity, he opens our eyes to
abuses and injustices in society and also the wider historical
perspective in which they can be placed," said the Academy.
</P>
<P>
The jury described Fo as "an extremely serious satirist with
multifaceted works."
</P>
<P>
Fo's main works include "Mistero Buffo" in 1969, "Accidental
Death of an Anarchist" in 1970, "We Can't Pay We Won't Pay!" in
1974 and "Trumpets and Raspberries" in 1981.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, however, Fo has been engaging in women issues
in several plays together with his wife.
</P>
<P>
"His strength is shown in the creation of texts which amuse,
engage and provide perspectives simultaneously," the Academy
said. "His oeuvre is of impressive artistic vitality range."
</P>
<P>
Born in 1926, Dario Fo received education in Academy of Arts in
Milan. And, his wife Franca Rame is also an actress and writer.
</P>
<P>
Each Nobel prize winner this year can get some 7.5 million
Swedish kronor (about 1 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Nobel prize was founded in the will of Alfred Nobel, a Swede
who invented dynamite and died in 1896. The prizes, along with
diplomas and gold medals, are presented to winners every year on
December 10, the anniversary of Nobel's death. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
