<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Officials Satisfied With Foreign Businesses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Chinese officials are generally
satisfied with the overall performance of overseas-funded
businesses in China, according to a survey released here today.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted by the public opinion research institute
under the People's University of China, was based on interviews
with 100 local and central officials and experts from policy study
institutes.
</P>
<P>
It focused on the current situation of overseas-funded
enterprises in the electronics industry and telecommunications
facilities manufacturing sector.
</P>
<P>
Over 70 percent of the respondents were satisfied with those
overseas-funded businesses' investment scale and their co-operation
with local businesses, said Liu Xiayang, deputy director of the
research institute.
</P>
<P>
Ninety-five of them share the view that overseas-funded
businesses should promote the import of technologies, which is of
critical importance to China's economic development at present.
</P>
<P>
The respondents also agreed that such businesses should further
improve their images in China by increasing investment, importing
more technological expertise and employing more Chinese natives as
their administrative personnel.
</P>
<P>
The survey also showed that "high-quality products",
"willingness to import advanced technology and management
expertise", "credibility", "large scale investment" should be the
major requirements for the most satisfactory overseas-funded
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
When asked to comment on the general performance of eight major
overseas-funded electronics and telecommunications enterprises in
China, the respondents put Motorola at the first place.
</P>
<P>
"Although only 100 people were interviewed in the survey, their
views reflected China's work of foreign economic co-operation over
the past decade," said Liu.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last June, China had approved more than 290,000
overseas-funded businesses, ranking second in using large amount
of overseas funds for four consecutive years, next only to the
United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
