<HEADLINE> Chinese, Tanzanian Defense Ministers Hold Talks in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Chi Haotian, vice-chairman of
the Central Military Commission, held talks today with visiting
Tanzanian Minister of Defense and National Services Maokola Majogo.
</P>
<P>
Chi expressed hope that Majogo's visit will promote friendship
and cooperation between the two countries and their armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Chi, who also serves as a state councillor and minister of
national defense, said that China values friendly relations with
Tanzania and other African nations. He said China hopes to work
closely with African nations to establish a long-term and stable
Sino-African relationship for the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
He noted that China and Tanzania enjoy a time-honored
friendship despite a wide geographical separation. He noted that
both are developing countries which have experienced identical
historical suffering and are now faced with the common task of
advancing their economies.
</P>
<P>
The two armed forces have maintained close cooperative
relations and military leaders from the two nations have engaged
in frequent exchange of visits, said Chi.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the Chinese People's Liberation Army (PLA) is
fully prepared to further strengthen friendship and cooperation
with the Tanzanian armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Chi briefed the Tanzanian visitors on China's domestic affairs
and efforts to build the PLA.
</P>
<P>
Majogo noted that Tanzania and China have a long history of
friendly cooperative relations, and he thanked the Chinese
government and people for their assistance over past decades.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the Tanzanian armed forces will expand
cooperation with the PLA. He said Tanzania appreciates China's
support for the third world countries and will continue to adhere
to the "one China" policy.
</P>
<P>
The two defense ministers also exchanged views on other issues
of common concern.
</P>
<P>
Majogo arrived here earlier today as Chi's guest. 
</P>
