<DOCNO> XIE19971009.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fruit with Medfly Barred Out of China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Quarantine officials at the
Beijing Capital Airport have seized some fruit bearing 28
Mediterranean fruit flies (medfly) carried by a foreign diplomat
to China, it was announced here today.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time that China has intercepted a big amount
of medflies hidden in fruit taken by a foreign embassy staff sent
to Beijing, said Yu Dahai, director of the Quarantine Bureau on
Animals and Plants under the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Beijing Capital Airport, the largest in China, has captured
medflies hidden in fruit carried by passengers from abroad.
</P>
<P>
Medfly, rated as the No. 1 killer of fruit, has spread to
more than 80 countries and regions, causing a direct economic
loss of tens of billions of US dollars. Therefore, many countries
have listed medfly on top of the destructive insects and strictly
forbid importing fruit from affected areas.
</P>
<P>
China is a bid agricultural state as well as large fruit
producer in the world. Once the insect is brought into China, it
would harm not only China's fruit production but also its fruit
trade with other countries, Yu said.
</P>
<P>
So far, China has not found a single case of medfly, African
hog cholera or mad cow disease as a result of a series protective
measures taken in the past decade and more, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Owing to interception of medfly at ports of entry on four
occasions, China will improve quarantine management of imported
farm produce, strictly control grain and meat import and prohibit
importing animals and products from countries with mad cow
disease and mouth-feet disease, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the country will tighten quarantine inspection on
goods, postal articles and packing materials carried by passengers
who come to China, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971009.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai PM Confident of Economic Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Thai Prime Minister
Chavalit Yongchaiyudh today expressed confidence in his country's
economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
"We aim to prove to the world that it is possible for Thailand
to excel economically, to experience great economic challenges,
and then to recover within two to three years," Chavalit told
Japanese business leaders at a luncheon meeting in Tokyo held by
the Japan Federation of Employers Associations (Nikkeiren).
</P>
<P>
Noting that Thailand has "a large domestic market with a
dynamic and active private sector" and "a well-trained and
adaptable labor force," the prime minister said these "strong
fundamentals will help us as we address the short-term problems in
our financial markets and meet the longer-term challenge of
rebuilding our international competitiveness."
</P>
<P>
Thailand is engaged in improving the investment environment and
make the country a better place for Japanese firms to do business,
the Thai prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
He called on Japanese business leaders to invest more in
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit arrived here Wednesday for a three-day visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
