<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKSAR Leader Speaks to HK General Chamber of Commerce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Tung Chee-hwa, Chief Executive
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR), stressed
here today the importance of China's growth and stability for Hong
Kong while urging the local businessmen to build Hong Kong into a
more prosperous region.
</P>
<P>
The strong and continued growth and stability of China is
fundamental to the prospects of Hong Kong, Tung said at a luncheon
hosted by the Hong Kong General Chamber of Commerce today, one
day after he made his first policy address.
</P>
<P>
Tung said that China's economic reform and opening up to the
world, which has been in progress successfully for almost 20
years, is a process that warms the hearts of all the people, and a
process that has given Hong Kong great opportunities.
</P>
<P>
"The scale of the development in China, and the fact that we
have an unmatchable location as a gateway to the south, gives us a
natural competitiveness advantages," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
"But we can not take it for granted that location alone will
ensure our prosperity," he added.
</P>
<P>
While the world economy is becoming increasingly open,
increasingly competitive, and ever more integrated through
information technology, Hong Kong has to embrace the new
technology and hone its competitiveness to keep it advantage, Tung
said.
</P>
<P>
But although constant change and improvement is needed in a
competitive market economy, stability is also essential, Tung
stressed.
</P>
<P>
Sound policies, consistently followed and managed openly and
honestly, are the basis for trust and confidence, which has been
one of Hong Kong's great competitive advantages.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong needs qualified, creative, motivated people to
upgrade its economy to meet the challenges of tomorrow, Tung
said. Therefore, the quality of Hong Kong's education system is of
great importance, he added.
</P>
<P>
The SAR government will be investing billions of dollars in
information technology in schools, not simply to teach children
how to use these vital tools, but to improve the teaching and
learning environment so as to stimulate creativity, Tung said.
</P>
<P>
"By our investment in people, information infrastructure and
physical infrastructure; by sound long term planning, and by close
attention to the efficiency of regulation and Government activity,
we will give you the tools, the framework and the freedom to
build Hong Kong into a truly great city," Tung concluded.
</P>
</TEXT>
