<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Education Secretaries Meet in Harare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 9 (Xinhua) --Permanent secretaries for
education from the Southern African Development Community (SADC)
Nations met here today to discuss ways to strengthen regional
cooperation in education.
</P>
<P>
The meeting being attended by secretaries from Angola,
Botswana, Lesotho, Malawi, Mauritius, Namibia, South Africa,
Swaziland, Tanzania, Zambia and Zimbabwe will support national
efforts at enhancing capacity in education policy analysis,
policy development, planning and management.
</P>
<P>
Discussions at the meeting will focus on the context and
background for the initiative to develop a regional cooperation
progranm, and country experience in formulating educational
policies.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony, Zimbabwe's Deputy Minister of Higher
Education and Technology Sikhanyiso Ndlovu said the initiative is
a way of improving the education system in the region.
</P>
<P>
He said recent studies had shown that the educational systems
in the region suffered from similar problems. Among the problems,
he said, are the high drop out rate, inability of the curricula
to respond to industrial needs, poor access to education by the
majority of people, shortage of qualified teachers in scientific
subjercts and declining resources allocated to education
training.
</P>
<P>
Ndlovu said there should be an exchange program for students
in the SADC region to enhance regional cooperation and improve
the education system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
