<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Official Proposes to Set up International </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia was today proposed
to set up an international news agency to help further enhance
the country's image throughout the world, Malaysian national news
agency Bernama reported today.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was made in Parliament today by Ruhanie Ahmad, a
government backbencher, during the debate on the Bernama
(Amendment) Bill 1997 which was tabled today suggesting for the
withdrawal of the exclusive rights of Bernama for the distribution
of foreign news in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Ruhanie said an international news agency owned by Malaysians
could help the government respond to attacks by the foreign media
which was bent on discrediting Malaysia's image.
</P>
<P>
Elaborating on his proposal for the setting up of the
international news agency, Ruhainie said "Such an agency can have
smart partnership with Third World news agencies. This is one way
of freeing ourselves from the clutches of the Western media and
western media capitalists."
</P>
<P>
He said such an agency could be easily set up, as the local
media had their respective representatives overseas.
</P>
<P>
He proposed that all media companies and Malaysian investors
pool their financial resources and energy to set up the Malaysian
International News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, tabling the Bernama (Amendment) Bill, Malaysian
Deputy Information Minister Suleiman Mohamed said that following
the unlimited entry of information and the creation of the
Multimedia Super Corridor (MSC), the government would not impose
any form of censorship on the flow of information.
</P>
<P>
He said the free flow of information was vital for the creation
of a well-informed society which could help in the overall
progress of the nation.
</P>
<P>
He said that rapid changes were taking place in the field of
information technology at present, rendering it impossible for
news to be channeled as in the past.
</P>
<P>
Bernama was set up under the Bernama Act 1967 which was amended
in 1990 to grant exclusive rights to Bernama to receive news
material from foreign news agencies and other organizations
dealing with news for distribution in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
With the present amendment, foreign news agencies could market
their services directly to subscribers in Malaysia or have
agreement with Bernama to market their products in this country.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
