<HEADLINE> India Reviews Policy on Foreign Direct Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government is
reviewing the policy on foreign direct investment (FDI) with a
view to removing some of the ambiguities in the existing policy on
foreign companies buying into Indian companies, an official said
here today.
</P>
<P>
The move is aimed at checking hostile takeovers of successfully
run Indian companies by their foreign competitors. This follows
the controversy over the British chemical and paint major ICI
PLc's purchase of 9.1 percent stake in India's Asian Paints.
</P>
<P>
The British multi-national company's deal struck in the
secondary market to pick up the stake of one of the four promoters
of Asian Paints is strongly opposed by the other three promoters.
</P>
<P>
The review would not only define hostile takeovers, but also is
intended at blocking hostile takeovers of successfully run Indian
companies, the same official said.
</P>
<P>
"We want foreign companies to bring in technology and
investments, to create jobs and wealth. In the specific case of
ICI PLc, they fit into neither of the four categories," the
official said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
