<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Remote Sensing Satellite on Sun-Synchronous </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The Indian remote sensing
satellite, IRS-ID, launched from the country's Tamil Nadu's
Sriharikota on September 29, has reached a sun-synchronous orbit
now, said a press release by the Indian Space Research
Organization (ISRO) in Bangalore today.
</P>
<P>
Indian scientists have been working hard to raise the perigee
to a height of 700 km. The propulsion system on board the
satellite is performing "very well".
</P>
<P>
Though the launch of IRS-ID was successful on September 29, the
satellite did not achieve the intended circular orbit, but was
moving in an elliptical orbit, with the perigee reaching as low as
300 km.
</P>
<P>
Since its launch, the process of raising the perigee of the
satellite had been progressing well in a step-by-step manner,
using the propellant in the satellite, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
All the systems on board the satellite were functioning well
and the three cameras on board were beaming high quality pictures.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
