<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-US Joint Commission on Commerce and Trade Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The 11th Session of the Sino-US
Joint Commission on Commerce and Trade (JCCT) ended here today.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation
Wu Yi and US Secretary of Commerce William Daley co-chaired the
closing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Wu and Daley expressed their belief that Sino-US commercial
cooperation will achieve greater success as a result of the
forthcoming historic summit between Chinese President Jiang
Zemin and US President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Wu said the session added a new page to the JCCT which is
the most important arena for commercial dialogue between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
She expressed the hope that the two nations will join their
efforts to advance the promising Sino-US commercial relations into
the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Wu noted that the two sides reached a series of important
agreements which will enable the JCCT to handle and solve a
greater number of issues.
</P>
<P>
Additional high-level meetings will be held at the ministerial
level in order expand dialogue and focus on trade concerns.
Government and embassy officials will also form joint working
groups in Beijing and Washington, and working business groups will
be formed to support the JCCT.
</P>
<P>
Wu announced that the JCCT has agreed to support the first
major finance seminar project in Beijing next spring, as well as
workshops on commercial law and export controls during the first
half of next year.
</P>
<P>
Wu said the workshops will help promote understanding between
China and US, and will greatly benefit the stable development of
Sino-US commercial relations.
</P>
<P>
History has proved that cooperation between China and US has
far outweighed conflicts, said Wu, adding that trade between
countries will continue to grow. She pointed to bright prospects
for greater understanding and cooperation between China, the
world's largest developing country, and the United States, the
world's largest developed nation.
</P>
<P>
Wu pointed out that certain problems are inevitable in
large-scale Sino-US commercial relations, and noted the importance
of making full use of the existing dialogue system and solving
emerging problems through consultations on an equal footing.
</P>
<P>
She stressed that the two countries should focus on the 21st
century, constructively deal with conflicts on the basis of
equality and mutual benefit, and introduce practical steps to
promote development.
</P>
<P>
Daley noted that this has been the most successful JCCT
session. He said it proved the JCCT is important to bilateral
commercial ties, and has laid a solid foundation for the Sino-US
Summit later this month.
</P>
<P>
Wu and Daley met the correspondents following the session.
</P>
<P>
Wu said the JCCT was held in a friendly, cordial and
practical manner.
</P>
<P>
Daley expressed satisfaction with his trip to China, and noted
that the two countries not only face certain problems and
challenges in terms of commercial relations, but also vast
opportunities. He said bilateral relations will continue to
develop smoothly so long as the two countries maintain dialogue
and contacts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
