<HEADLINE> Flower Display on Tian'anmen Square Extended to Mid-October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Four pots of blooming bauhinia
braving chilly breeze of Beijing's early autumn make gardening
expert Zhang Fubao feeling very proud.
</P>
<P>
The regional symbol flower of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region is placed with other 200,000 pots of flowers
on National Day's Tian'anmen Square to signify Hong Kong's return
to China on July 1. Its premier at the Chinese capital attracts
millions of people to come to watch.
</P>
<P>
But what mostly pleases Zhang is that he and his colleagues
successfully delay the florescence of this tropical plant to
September and October, in order to celebrate the opening of the
15th National Congress of the Chinese Communist Party on September
12 and the National Day on October 1.
</P>
<P>
"The most important and difficult thing (to build those large
floral mosaics) is to unify the blossom period of different
flowers," says Zhang, s senior engineerer of the Beijing Flowers
and Trees Company.
</P>
<P>
Workers at the company use many measures to fulfill the aim,
such as lowering the temperature, increasing or reducing
illumination in greenhouses, and using fertilizers, Zhang says.
</P>
<P>
Huge floral mosaics, fountains and lighting display on the
square around every National Day have come to be Beijing's most
attractive sightseeing spot since 1986, when the country
celebrated its 37th birthday.
</P>
<P>
Gardening workers usually deploy tens of thousands of potted
flowers from greenhouses to arrange them into various shapes in
the mid-September. The displaying period only lasts for some 20
days due to factors such as climate.
</P>
<P>
"But this year's work started from September 1 because of the
Party Congress," Zhang says, adding that the show time will last
until mid-October.
</P>
<P>
"We'll set a record in keeping the longest flower-display
period on Tian'anmen Square," Zhang says proudly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
