<HEADLINE> S. Leone's Military Building Attacked by Nigerian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Soldiers using pickaxes and
earthmoving equipment are searching the collapsed building at the
Military Headquarters in Sierra Leone which were attacked by
Nigerian jet from ECOMOG on Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
The attack, according to state radio and TV, killed four
people including two soldiers, but independent reports put the
figure at up to 60 killed.
</P>
<P>
State radio also said 28 people including civilians were badly
injured, many of them hovering between life and death.
</P>
<P>
The military buildings, constructed seven years ago, were
extensively damaged.
</P>
<P>
A defense spokesman said, "the search will continue for some
time as up to 10 more soldiers have not been accounted for. They
may have been buried under the debris."
</P>
<P>
Residents in the area reported that the aircraft flew to the
area from the mountain tops adjacent to the military complex and
released seven rockets which hit the frontage of the building in
a dense black smoke.
</P>
<P>
A senior military officer said the attack may have been
prompted by a scheduled meeting at the headquarters which would
have been attended by the military leader, Major Johnny Paul
Koroma. The venue of the meeting was changed at the last minute.
</P>
</TEXT>
