<HEADLINE> Designer Explains WTO Logo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The new World Trade Organization
(WTO) logo is a hint of the globe, which is suggested by six
graphic arcs symbolizing member nations to forge strategic
alliances, Su Yeang, the logo's original designer said.
</P>
<P>
"Dynamism and optimism prevail as the swirls integrate,
encapsulating the WTO's united spirit of promoting fair and open
trade," Yeang said. Further strengthened by the "World Trade
Organization" embracing the globe, the organization's
responsibilities as the guardian and management consultant of
international trade are successfully reinforced.
</P>
<P>
Colors selected are bright and vibrant, in red, blue and green,
representing the major colors of the international flags of WTO
members, the designer said.
</P>
<P>
She added that the logo can be used in information kits,
conference bags, security passes, posters, banners, billboards,
stage design, media and delegate handbooks.
</P>
<P>
The logo, with six arcs in red, blue and green, is adapted from
the logo originally commissioned by the government of Singapore
for the WTO's first Ministerial Conference hosted by the country
last December. In April 1997, the WTO General Council accepted
Singapore's offer to transfer the logo and its copyright to the
WTO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
