<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa, France Sign Memo on Political Dialogue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 9 (Xinhua) -- South Africa and France
today signed a memorandum of understanding to set up a forum for
political dialogue between the two countries, the South African
Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
The document was signed in Cape Town by South African Foreign
Minister Alfred Nzo and his French counterpart, Hubert Vedrine,
who is in South Africa for a short visit.
</P>
<P>
The forum will enable annual meetings between French and South
African foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, expert groups on bilateral relations,
multilateral cooperation and other international issues of common
interest are to be set up.
</P>
<P>
"This memorandum of understanding creates a formal mechanism
permitting the two governments to regularly exchange views on
international affairs," a statement of South Africa's Foreign
Affairs Department said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also agreed to cooperate in the training of
young diplomats.
</P>
<P>
The two men also signed an agreement under which France is to
give South Africa 13 million Rand (2.8 million U.S. Dollars) to
help with the transformation of South Africa's educational
system.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine said the two agreements made concrete a will on the
part of the two countries to cooperate not only on a bilateral
level, but also in the areas of politics and economics.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine, who arrived in Cape Town this morning for his first
visit to South Africa as foreign minister, is expected to hold
talks with South African Deputy President Thabo Mbeki and address
South African parliament's Foreign Relations Committee to unveil
Paris's newly revised policy toward Africa.
</P>
<P>
The new policy plan is expected to include a reduction of
French intervention in African conflicts, a determination to
pursue multilateral rather than solitary actions, a diminished
military presence on the continent and a much closer relationship
with South Africa.
</P>
<P>
France had traditionally maintained close relationships with
French-speaking African countries.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine is also scheduled to open a French business center in
Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
"South Africa and France enjoy well established diplomatic
relations and excellent cooperation in the fields of trade and
industry, culture, science and technology," the Foreign Ministry
statement said.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's imports from France last year was 4 billion
Rand (850 million Dollars) and exports to the country was 3
billion Rand (640 million Dollars), according to a French embassy
spokesman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
