<HEADLINE> Malaysia Continues to Welcome Foreign Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia will continue with
its privatization program, deregulation, liberalization and more
importantly to be responsive to the views of the business
community including genuine foreign investors, Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad said here today.
</P>
<P>
He pledged that Malaysia will continue to welcome foreign
investors and investors from Britain and Europe will find in this
country a business-friendly government, a market-driven economy, a
pro active private sector and a buoyant optimism.
</P>
<P>
"As a pragmatic government, we have instituted remedial
measures to reduce our expenditure, defer the big projects, reduce
costs and boost productivity so that we can continue our economic
progress," he said in a message in conjunction with the London
Dialogue on the theme "Malaysia and Britain - Dynamic Partnership
for the 21st Century" to be held in London on October 21.
</P>
<P>
He said "Despite recent turmoil in the financial markets,
Malaysia remains an attractive investment."
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said the government has taken bold steps to overcome
the currency and stock market crisis.
</P>
<P>
"While we may slow down slightly next year, I am confident that
we shall still achieve moderately high growth with low inflation,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
For the first half of this year, Malaysia achieved an 8.7 per
cent growth.
</P>
<P>
On the forthcoming dialogue, Mahathir said it is timely not
only to facilitate open and frank discussion on bilateral issues
but also to enable British businessmen, fund managers and
institutional investors to obtain first-hand information on the
current state of the Malaysian economy.
</P>
<P>
The dialogue is organized by Malaysia's Asian Strategy and
Leadership Institute (ASLI) with the cooperation of the
British-Malaysian Society, Asia House and the Malaysian
Commonwealth Studies Center, Cambridge University, and is expected
to be attended by some 300 top corporate leaders from both
countries, according to official sources here.
</P>
