<HEADLINE> China, New Zealand Jointly Issue Flower Stamps </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 9 (Xinhua) -- China's Ministry of Post and
Telecommunications (MPT) and New Zealand Post announced here today
the joint issue of a set of flower stamps, the first of such issue
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The new set includes two stamps, with one featuring Chinese
Rugosa roses, and the other, the New Zealand's Aotearoa.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Guizheng from China and Paul Martison, two designers of
the stamp set, created a pattern that the leaves of the two roses
intertwin with each other, "symbolizing the friendly cooperation
between the post offices of the two countries, and the lasting
friendship between the two peoples," said a spokesman for MPT at
today's issue ceremony.
</P>
<P>
According to him, it is the eighth time for MPT to jointly
issue stamps with foreign countries following Canada, the United
States, Thailand, Australia, San Marino, Singapore and Sweden.
</P>
<P>
A similar ceremony was held today in Wellington, capital of New
Zealand. 
</P>
