<HEADLINE> Internet Development to be Discussed in Eastern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Telecommunications
ministers and information technology experts from eastern Africa
are to gather here from October 13-15 for a regional seminar on
the development of Internet infrastructure in the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release jointly issued by the United
Nations Economic Commission for Africa (ECA) and the United
Nations Development Program (UNDP), the seminar will be organized
by the the UNDP's Regional Bureau for Africa (UNDP/RBA) and the
ECA.
</P>
<P>
The seminar is aimed to facilitate sharing country
experiences, taking stock of progress in Internet connectivity,
assessing Internet services and their impact on development and
mapping out future plans to support Internet development in the
sub-region.
</P>
<P>
The release said, it is one of a series of sub-regional
seminars planned under the UNDP's Internet initiative for Africa,
a multi-million Dollar, three-year project aimed at establishing
Internet services and enhancing those currently available in 12
sub-Saharan African countries.
</P>
<P>
It also falls under the umbrella of ECA's African information
society initiative, a comprehensive framework for the building of
a development-serving African information infrastructure, and the
harnessing information technology for development component of
the UN system-wide special initiative on Africa.
</P>
<P>
Telecommunications ministers from Ethiopia, Burundi, Kenya,
Rwanda, Tanzania and Uganda will make presentations on the
situation in their respective countries, the press release added.
</P>
