<HEADLINE> China's Industrial Production Up Steadily </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 9 (Xinhua) -- China's industrial production
grew steadily in the first nine months of this year, with an
overall improvement in economic performance, and achieved an added
value of 1,480 billion yuan, up 11 percent over the same period of
1996.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, state enterprises achieved 853.9 billion yuan in
added value, an increase of 7.4 percent against the figure of the
corresponding period of last year. State industrial firms
registered a 5.4 percent rise in the added value.
</P>
<P>
These are revealed by the latest monthly report issued by the
State Statistical Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The report says that the market regulation is now playing an
increasingly big role, along with the progress in the
restructuring of the mix of industrial products.
</P>
<P>
The production of energy products and major raw materials had
been growing at a low speed, due to huge stockpiles.
</P>
<P>
In the first nine months, China turned out a total of 930
million tons of standard coal, up 2.3 percent, and in the
meantime, major raw materials like sulphuric acid, thick nitric
acid, coke, cement and steel plate increased by 3.1-8.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The sales of daily necessities and household electric
appliances had experienced ups and downs for different
products. The output of washing machines, vacuum cleaners,
refrigerators, air-conditioners, electric cookers, color
television sets and audio sets surged by 8-36.2 percent, while
these of cigarettes, silk, bicycles, electric fans and cameras
dropped by 3.1-8.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the first nine months, the production-sales ratio for the
country's 370,000 industrial enterprises was 95.31 percent, 0.6
percentage points higher than that in the same period of last
year, the report says.
</P>
<P>
In the third quarter, the production-sales ratio went up to 96
percent and above, which was quite high compared with figures in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
The report says that in the first eight months, the index for
the economic performance of the country's industrial enterprises was
87.5 percent, and these enterprises generated a total pre-tax
profit of 327.7 billion yuan, a 15 percent increase compared with
the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
However, the report points out, state-owned small enterprises
are still facing many problems, and the firms in the red are still
suffering from losses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971009.0142 </DOCNO>
