<HEADLINE> Israeli Military Chief to Visit Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Defense Forces Chief of
Staff Amnon Shahak is expected to pay a three-day visit to Turkey
to enhance military cooperation, the local newspaper Daily News
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Shahak will arrive here on Sunday and start talks with his
Turkish counterpart Ismail Hakki Karadayi and the top military
brass the next day, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
He will also meet with Turkish President Suleyman Demirel, it
said, quoting senior officials from the Turkish General Staff who
declined to be named.
</P>
<P>
The two sides are expected to take up the date and other
specific arrangements concerning much-publicized joint naval
exercises of Israel, Turkey and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The three-way naval drill off the Israeli Mediterranean coast
had originally been set in May and was postponed to November
16. But reports had it that the U.S. wanted it to be further put
off until next January.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli embassy here was not available for comment on the
upcoming visit.
</P>
<P>
Rapidly growing military cooperation has been witnessed between
Turkey and Israel, which signed two agreements last year to allow,
among other things, the warplanes of each country to be trained in
the other's airspace.
</P>
<P>
This irked neighboring Arab countries, which condemned Turkey,
a predominantly Muslim country, of betraying the interests of the
Muslim world.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will also discuss other defense issues including
Israel's assistance in modernizing Turkey's fighter planes and
joint training of their troops, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
