<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drinking Water Project For South China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The Tujia and Miao
Nationalities Autonomous Prefecture in a remote and backward
mountainous part of China's Hunan province have had some success
in improving the rural drinking water situation.
</P>
<P>
According to rural water improvement officials, since 1990,
some 1.51 million rural people, or 74 percent of the region's
people, have benefited from the project, and 1.22 million local
people have access to tap-water and 296,000 are using wells.
</P>
<P>
A total of 37 million yuan from local government, institutions,
and other sources has been spent on the project. In some places
that were not covered by the government water project villagers
raised funds themselves and received free technical assistance
from local water-conservation departments and public health
departments.
</P>
<P>
The officials say that a shortage of potable water in these
mountainous areas has not only made things hard on local farmers
but is also a major cause of infectious diseases.
</P>
<P>
Xiang Shilin, the commissioner of the autonomous prefecture,
told Xinhua that the project has been a means of preventing the
spread of water-borne disease and has played a positive role in
eliminating poverty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971009.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Has No Intention to Disrupt WTO Negotiations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Deputy Prime
Minister Anwar Ibrahim today clarified that Malaysia's stand was
that it would not disrupt World Trade Organization (WTO)
negotiations on trade in financial services in Geneva on December
15 this year.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has no intention of disrupting the talks in any way,
but what it wants to do is to defend its interests as well as that
of emerging economies, Anwar, who is also Finance Minister, said
here after a function.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said that Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad's outspokenness
against curbing currency speculation had got the attention of the
world.
</P>
<P>
"We are not asking the world to pay attention to Kuala Lumpur
alone but to safeguard the interests of Third World countries and
those which are rapidly developing including ASEAN," Anwar said.
</P>
<P>
He said that WTO Director-General Renato Ruggiero telephoned
him last night requesting for information relating to Malaysia's
recent proposal for regulations on currency trading, aimed at
curbing currency speculation which adversely affected ASEAN
economies.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said that he also received a fax message from the World
Bank requesting for Malaysia's views to discuss the currency
problems affecting Malaysia and other ASEAN countries.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund (IMF), which met this week, has
also asked for Malaysia's views to study rules and regulations
relating to currency speculation, he said.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said that WTO officials including Ruggiero are scheduled
to visit Malaysia at the end of this month to obtain feedback on
Malaysia's proposal.
</P>
<P>
"In my opinion, the proposal and the calls by the prime
minister, which, though initially, shocked the world, seems to
have abated. They now accept our proposals and acknowledge our
resolve to further liberalize our markets," he said.
</P>
<P>
Anwar reiterated that the government did not intend to change
existing rules on currency trading in the country.
</P>
<P>
He said that the current arrangements would be examined based
on information and a joint review would be made by IMF and World
Bank officials who would be talking with local officials in a few
days' time.
</P>
<P>
"We have agreed to continue efforts to liberalize, but we do
not want liberalization to bring about losses to developing
countries or that their interests could be undermined easily," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said that regulations were needed to safeguard the interests
and economies of developing countries and that these countries
should not be exploited just for profits as that done by
speculators. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971009.0148 </DOCNO>
