<HEADLINE> Japan Hopes to Resume Normalization Talks With DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Foreign Minister Keizo
Obuchi today expressed hope that the Democratic People's Republic
of Korea (DPRK) would engage in normalization talks with Japan
under the leadership of Kim Jong Il.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Obuchi also hoped the DPRK will
proceed with the normalization talks "with the exercise of more
leadership" under Kim Jong Il, who assumed the top post of the
Workers Party of Korea Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Japan will make the utmost efforts toward (holding) the
normalization talks at the earliest possible time," he said as a
response to the DPRK's announcement Wednesday that Kim Jong Il was
officially elected general secretary of the party.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto also
expressed the wish that Kim Jong Il's formal election will help
improve relations between Japan and DPRK.
</P>
<P>
Talks aimed at normalizing bilateral ties between the two
countries began in January 1991, but broke off in November 1992
without achieving any specific progress. 
</P>
