<HEADLINE> SAR Government Confident in Fulfilling Policy Targets: Tung </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) Tung Chee Hwa said
today that the government has determination and confidence in
materializing various objectives set out in his policy address.
</P>
<P>
Present in a phone-in program of the Radio Television Hong Kong
(RTHK) early this morning, Tung answered dozens of calls from
ordinary Hong Kong residents on the policy address he delivered
yesterday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
On questions related to housing, which is a primary concern of
local society, Tung said that the policy address has laid down
general housing targets, and the SAR government will spare no
effort to turn them into a reality.
</P>
<P>
The basic solution to the housing issue is increasing the
supply of land so that the property price would turn steady and
see a "soft landing", he added.
</P>
<P>
On the political structure of the HKSAR, the chief executive
pointed out that the Basic Law has shaped the democratic
development process of Hong Kong and provided legal guarantee for
democracy and freedom of the local people.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out the government will, in accordance with
principles set in the Basic Law, work out detailed arrangements
for Hong Kong's democratic development.
</P>
<P>
Democratic development will proceed in an orderly way toward
the long-term objective of having the chief executive and the
legislature elected by universal suffrage, he said.
</P>
<P>
Maintaining and enhancing economic competitiveness is another
focal point of Tung's maiden policy address.
</P>
<P>
The address proposed intensified efforts to develop high-tech
and high value-added industries so that Hong Kong's competitive
edge and economic vitality would be maintained, Tung said.
</P>
<P>
The hotline program was broadcast live in Cantonese, Putonghua
and English.
</P>
<P>
Last night Tung attended a live televised panel discussion
organized by the RTHK, answering questions from representatives of
trade, media, youth, education and other sectors.  
</P>
</TEXT>
