<DOCNO> XIE19971009.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone Junta Accuses UN of Being Biased </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The military junta in Sierra
Leone has said the United Nations Security Council's decision on
sanctions against the country is unfortunate and biased.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council announced the sanctions on Wednesday,
calling on the military junta "to take immediate steps to restore
democracy in Sierra Leone."
</P>
<P>
The sanctions, however, will hurt the "poor Sierra Leonean
civilians," said Aliu Kamara, spokesman of Sierra Leone's current
supreme Armed Forced Revolutionary Council (AFRC), Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Kamara's views were shared by an AFRC member, Sam Bakare, who
said the council was biased against Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
"We are not worried about the sanctions. I can tell you that
the sanctions will not affect us as along as we have our
resources like diamond and gold, but it will affect the poor
innocent civilians of this country," Bakare said, quoted by press
reports today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kamara warned that the forces loyal to the junta
would attack the west African peacekeeping force (ECOMOG), which
is enforcing an economic embargo on Sierra Leone ordered by the
sub-regional leaders.
</P>
<P>
"We are definitely going to attack ECOMOG positions if this is
what it makes the international community to understand that
Sierra Leone is being bombarded and harassed by Nigeria," the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria is leading the ECOMOG operations to enforce the
economic embargo to force the junta to return power to the
civilian government ousted in the May 25 coup.
</P>
<P>
According to Kamara, ECOMOG jets hit the powerhouse of the
military headquarters at about 2:00 Wednesday afternoon, and
repeated the attack two hours later, with the main building hit
and many people suffered.
</P>
<P>
"We are appealing to members of the international community
that Nigeria has gone beyond extreme and we are not going to
swallow this anymore. We are definitely going to defend our
territorial integrity," he said.
</P>
<P>
Claiming that Nigeria overstepped its peace enforcement
mandate with the bombardment, Kamara said: "As far as Nigeria is
concerned, the situation between Nigeria and Sierra Leone has
resulted into a state of war."
</P>
<P>
He also accused the international community of treating the
junta with disrepute, saying that the coup the military launched
in May "is not a haphazard coup", but one based on things.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he reiterated that the junta remained open to
negotiations with the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS) while expecting the international community to come in
and negotiate the situation.
</P>
<P>
The UN decision on sanctions received welcome in Nigeria and
the toppled civilian government of Sierra Leone, which have been
seeking immediate ousting of the junta since the coup.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers of the five ECOWAS countries championing the
restoration of Sierra Leone's ousted government are to meet today
in Abuja, capital of Nigeria, to discuss the situation with the
long-expected UN punitive measures on the junta.
</P>
<P>
The ECOWAS Committee of Five, composed of Nigeria, Guinea,
Ghana, Cote d'Ivoire and Liberia, are coordinating the ECOWAS
objective of reinstating President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah who was
removed in the coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
