<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971009.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Likely to Increase Gas Price </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government is
actively considering increase of gas price by over 15 percent from
next month, sources from the Energy Ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
The increase has become inevitable as the government is
committed to purchasing gas from private gas field developers from
April next year at a rate nearly double the current price, the
sources explained.
</P>
<P>
The average price of gas per unit (1,000 cubic feet = 304.8
cubic meters) is now 55 taka (about 1.24 U.S. dollars) and will
rise to about 63 taka (about 1.42 dollars) if the decision is
taken.
</P>
<P>
The government will purchase gas from private gas field
developers at a rate of about 90 taka (about 2.03 dollars) per
unit, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
If the government does not increase the price of gas now, it
will have to subsidize the gas to be purchased from Cairn in April
next and Occidental sometime later.
</P>
<P>
The government has plans to increase gas price by about 80
percent by the year 2001, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
However, they said, if the government does not increase the gas
price immediately, it will be severely affected by a liquidity
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The government will purchase 75 billion cubic feet (about 2.25
million cubic meters) during 1998-99 at a cost of 67.57 dollars.
About 260 billion cubic feet (about 7.80 million cubic meters) of
gas is now consumed in the country.
</P>
<P>
The gas price will be increased in four phases in the next four
years. The price of gas will be re-fixed at 64.77 taka (about 1.46
dollars) per unit next year, 86.09 taka (about 1.94 dollars) in
1999, 88.15 taka (about 1.99 dollars) in 2000 and 89.76 taka
(about 2.02 dollars) in 2001, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
Gas price increase will have far-reaching impact on power
plants and fertilizer factories which account for nearly 80
percent of the natural gas consumed in the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971009.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Dario Fo Wins Nobel Literature Prize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Italian playwright Dario Fo
won the 1997 Nobel Literature Prize, the Swedish Academy announced
today. 
</P>
