<DOCNO> XIE19971009.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Fall After Greenspan's Comments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
dived more than 1.6 percent today on the back of fears of a
United States economic contraction and improved job figures which
dampened hopes for a local interest rate cut.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index lost 46.2 points to 2722.2.
</P>
<P>
The fall came after Wall Street fell one percent on comments by
U.S. Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan which foreshadowed
increased wages, inflation and interest rates.
</P>
<P>
"There was some nervousness about what Alan Greenspan had to
say which saw Wall Street fall and spread to our market this
morning," Steve Mayne from Nevitts said.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) reported a strong
rebound of 74,700 new jobs last month, more than compensating for
the 38,200 jobs which disappeared in August.
</P>
<P>
Banking stocks were particularly hit by the news. National
Australia Bank shares fell 89.6 cents, ANZ lost 22 cents, Westpac
fell 14.2 cents and Commonwealth finished 20.5 cents lower.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index shed 81 points to 4475.5 while the
all resources fell 18.2 points to 1342.8.
</P>
<P>
Market bellwether BHP emerged better than most from today's
difficult day, losing just 15 cents to 15.92 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Other resources heavyweights Rio Tinto and WMC did not fare as
well, with Rio falling 59.9 cents and WMC dropping 21 cents.
</P>
<P>
The gold sector performed well against the market today, with
the index losing only 0.7 points to 1334.2. Gold was traded at
2.25 U.S. dollars per ounce higher at 334.00 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover today was 337.4 million shares at a value of
997 million Australian dollars (722.8 million U.S. dollars), with
falls outnumbering rises 793 to 361. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
