<HEADLINE> Labor Exports From North Chinese City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, October 9 (Xinhua) -- North China's port city of
Tianjin has had rapid development in its labor exports, earning
some 100 million US dollars from the service business since the
beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
The city, which has a population of nearly 10 million, has more
than 10,000 people working abroad, mainly in the countries of East
and Southeast Asia, and the Middle East. It has sent 6,800 people
abroad for labor this year.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin is rich in labor resources, experts say, with a fairly
high level of training and comparatively low costs. In order to
improve its labor service, it has provided greater training in
technology and languages for personnel who are likely to work
abroad.
</P>
<P>
More technicians are working in labor export programs,
officials say, the bulk in construction and tailoring.
</P>
<P>
"Priority will be given to large-scale technology-intensive
projects," one official with the municipal government says.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
