<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTO Adopts Logo After Three Years' Absence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The World Trade Organization
(WTO) today officially unveiled its logo, which has been absent
since the organization came into being in January 1, 1995.
</P>
<P>
The logo, with six arcs in red, blue and green, is adapted from
the logo initially commissioned for the WTO's first Ministerial
Conference hosted by Singapore last December.
</P>
<P>
Its adoption "is another step in establishing this unique
institution on a firm and lasting foundation," said WTO
Director-General Renato Ruggiero, who unveiled the logo at a
ceremony held at the WTO headquarters here.
</P>
<P>
"It is the visual representation of a dynamic organization with
a vital role to play in ensuring the continued and rules-based
expansion of trade worldwide," Ruggiero said.
</P>
<P>
In April, the WTO General Council accepted Singapore's offer to
transfer to the WTO the logo and its copyright.
</P>
<P>
"A hint of the globe," said the logo's original designer Ms. Su
Yeang, "is suggested by the six graphic arcs symbolizing world
trade with member nations meeting to forge strategic alliances."
</P>
<P>
Su Yeang, who owns a Singapore-based graphic arts company named
after her, further explained that "dynamism and optimism prevail
as the swirls integrate, encapsulating the WTO's united spirit of
promoting fair and open trade."
</P>
<P>
In mid May 1998, the WTO will hold its second Ministerial
Conference in Geneva and celebrate the 50th anniversary of the
multilateral trade system existing since the WTO's precedent, the
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT), was founded.
</P>
<P>
Currently, a total of 132 countries and regions are members of
the organization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
