<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Sails Up on Jobs Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar closed
almost one and half U.S. cents higher today, sailing on a wind of
optimism blown up by better-than-expected news on jobs growth.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar ended at 73.87 U.S. cents, sharply
stronger from 72.47 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The September data from the Australian Bureau of Statistics
published today showed total employment leaped by 74,700 in the
month, almost doubling the average market forecast of a 43,200
advance, and the unemployment rate was 0.1 percent lower at 8.6
per cent.
</P>
<P>
The foreign exchange market greeted the news with a rush of
buying activity fueled by expectations among players that the
Reserve Bank of Australia will not ease monetary policy in the
short term.
</P>
<P>
"The market has taken the short term view that any rate cut is
not going to be in the next few days," said IBJ Australia senior
foreign exchange manager Shane Spurway.
</P>
<P>
Spurway said that the Australian dollar's upward move above
73.40 U.S. cents to an intra-day session high of 73.98 likely
signals the start of a small upward trend.
</P>
<P>
"So it should continue on and have a sniff around that 75 U.S.
cent level over the next week or so. But it all depends really on
the economic numbers coming out in the next two months," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was at 89.48 Japanese yen, up from 88.66,
and at 1.2921 German marks, up from 1.2761.  
</P>
</TEXT>
