<HEADLINE> World Bank President to Visit Pakistan Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 9 (Xinhua) -- World Bank President James D.
Wolfensohn will make a five-day visit to Pakistan starting from
October 18, official sources said today.
</P>
<P>
The tour by Wolfensohn, who will also visit Bangladesh, will
highlight the achievements and challenges of development in South
Asia, sources from the World Bank Office here said.
</P>
<P>
Economic reforms taking root across the region are stimulating
strong growth and investment and social indicators are slowly
improving.
</P>
<P>
But South Asia remains one of the poorest regions having the
largest concentration of poor in the world, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
Following Africa, South Asia is the largest regional recipient
of concessional lending from the International Development
Association (IDA), the World Bank's affiliate that provides
interest-free loans to the world's poorest countries.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan and Bangladesh are among the top recipients of IDA
funds. Pakistan is also a substantial borrower from the
International Bank for Reconstruction Development, the World
Bank's main lending arm which provides loans at near-commercial
terms, the sources explained.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Wolfensohn will meet with representatives of
business, non-governmental organizations, politicians as well as
the media.
</P>
<P>
He will look at both World Bank-supported and other development
projects and interact with direct beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
The visit will highlight important themes of the Bank's work
such as forging partnerships with civil society, fostering
community participation in development projects, broadening access
and improving the quality of social services to the poor, battling
corruption, and promoting sound macroeconomic management and
banking systems.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
