<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Father Found for One-Year-Old Giant Panda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 9 (Xinhua) -- A male panda named Liang Liang
has finally been identified as the father of a one-year-old female
giant panda just as the cub began to meet visitors in the Beijing
Zoo.
</P>
<P>
It has puzzled zoo keepers as to who, among three potential
ones, was the real father of Jing Xin ever since the baby panda
was born on October 4 last year.
</P>
<P>
The white streaks on both hind legs of Jing Xin, identical to
those on Liang Liang's body, enabled zoo keepers to conclude that
Liang Liang is the father because the pattern of the streaks on the
hind legs of a panda is the most crucial body feature decided by
genes, explained Zhang Jinguo, deputy director of the Beijing Zoo.
</P>
<P>
He added that other similarities between the two also
contributed to the identification.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said: "it is very important to know who the real father
is so that inbreeding among pandas will be prevented in the
future, and more healthy panda cubs will be born."
</P>
<P>
The cub's mother Le Le, during her estrus cycle last spring,
mated three times with a male partner Ying Ying, two times with
Liang Liang, and was artificially inseminated with the germ of
another male called Lin Nan.
</P>
<P>
Le Le gave birth to two cubs on October 4 last year, but only
Jing Xin survived, who is also the sole surviving panda cub born in
Chinese zoos last year. Born with a weight of just 120 grams, the
baby panda now weighs 40 kilograms.
</P>
<P>
The giant panda is one of the most endangered species on
earth. There are only some 1,000 surviving pandas today, most of
them living in western China's Sichuan, Gansu and Shaanxi
provinces.
</P>
<P>
A mature female panda can get pregnant once a year if she
successfully mates with a male during the three-to-five-day estrus
period, and can produce one or two cubs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971009.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation to Go Up in India Later This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 9 (Xinhua) -- India's annual rate of
inflation is likely to surge in the second half of 1997-98
financial year (April 1,1997 - March 31, 1998), a senior official
said here today.
</P>
<P>
"Inflation will go up in the second half of the current year as
we assume that the increase in cost will be passed on," he said.
</P>
<P>
October-March is likely to witness a seven percent average
inflation as there has been an increase in money supply at 16
percent in the first half of 1997-98, which has been more than the
targeted level of 15.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The indirect impact of petroleum price hike has still not flown
into the system, the official said. This year is likely to end
with an average inflation of about six percent.
</P>
<P>
The projected annual average inflation of six percent is one of
the lowest since the economy was opened up in the early 1990s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
