<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Castro Addresses Communist Party Congress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Cuban leader Fidel Castro today
vowed to push ahead policies for the country's economic recovery
despite tightened U.S. economic embargo.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. economic embargo further stepped up in recent years
made it more difficult for Cuba to survive the changes following
the disintegration of the former Soviet Union, Castro said.
</P>
<P>
But the Cuban people, he told the opening session of a
Communist Party national congress, didn't bow to the U.S. pressure
and instead meet the challenge with a series of solutions.
</P>
<P>
Castro, the first secretary of the Communist Party, made the
remarks in front of the 1,500 delegates to the 5th party congress.
</P>
<P>
In a seven-hour speech, he reviewed what happened inside and
outside Cuba in the past six years after the 4th party national
congress in 1991, and what the party did to keep the economy going.
</P>
<P>
The disintegration of the Soviet Union and the East European
socialist bloc, Castro said, ended the energy and raw materials
supplies, as well as most of the market accesses, for Cuba.
</P>
<P>
With the manufacturing sector being paralyzed, the economy
plunged into a severe crisis, he noted, adding that its gross
domestic product (GDP) was down 34 percent between 1991 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
Then, a series of new policies of the government, led by the
party, came to the rescue, reversing the downward trend in 1994
and boosting the GDP growth to a projected 2-3 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
The measures included expanding the tourism sector, encouraging
foreign capital inflow, allowing Cuban citizens to keep hard
currencies, and easing restrictions on self-employees, he said.
</P>
<P>
Also as this Caribbean island's president, Castro condemned the
continued U.S. hostility, alleging that all of the 20 recent cases
of sabotage in Cuba were "organized and supplied" from the United
States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
