<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fu Mingxia Makes No Splash in National Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 9 (Xinhua) -- When Barcelona Olympic champion
Sun Shuwei paced ace divers Yu Zhuocheng and Lan Wei to win the
men's team gold medal for Guangdong province, people harbored the
idea that diving in the National Games is to become the showcase
for the veterans.
</P>
<P>
The trend may well prove to be true, with the exception for Fu
Mingxia, the world's most successful diver in the 1990s, who has
stepped away from the pool after making a golden double in the
Atlanta Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
In the women's 10-meter platform on Monday, a fortress Fu has
held for years, Wang Rui, a native of Beijing, stole the limelight
by taking home the gold medal, declaring the end of Fu's dynasty.
</P>
<P>
The 19-year-old Fu was expected to replace American legend Greg
Louganis as the all-time greatest diver, but the triple Olympic
champion halted her illustrious career by herself, becoming an
bystander from a heroine.
</P>
<P>
She jumped to fame in Barcelona at age 13, throwing herself
from the 10-meter platform, flipping and twisting her body for
straight-down perfect dives in the 1992 Olympic Games wherein she
became the youngest to win an Olympic platform gold medal.
</P>
<P>
In Atlanta, Fu Mingxia became one of the great athletes of the
time by clinching double golds on both platform and springboard.
The Chinese woman is only one gold shy of the record of four
shared by Pat McCormack and Greg Louganis, both of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
The child of Barcelona who will turn out to 22 in Sydney, has
surprisingly become a controversial figure by stirring up "the
retirement dispute" only 13 months after her Atlanta glory.
</P>
<P>
Last year, she submitted her retirement application to the
national diving team, making a big impact upon the diving circle
in the country.
</P>
<P>
"I'm tired, I don't want to dive on," said the teenager diving
star who was tipped to repeat her feat in the Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
On her part, Fu complained that she had long been plagued with
injuries to her legs, shoulders and waist, and she was afraid of
paralysis, a dire possibility in more tough trainings and
competitions.
</P>
<P>
Although the national squad badly needs a veteran as the
coreforce in the international arena before the debutants become
mature in their skills and experience, Fu, now majors in economics
in Qinghua University, insisted that she couldn't return to the
pool for another span of time.
</P>
<P>
The Olympic champion whose smile won over the world in Atlanta,
said that "only I myself alone know how much I had suffered in the
four years after the Barcelona Games. I'm too exausted, I have no
choice but to quit." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
