<DOCNO> XIE19971009.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 19th South East Asian Games to Open on Saturday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The 19th South East Asian Games
are scheduled to open here on Saturday with more than 4,300
athletes from 10 nations to attend.
</P>
<P>
Concerns about smog, mosquitoes and facilities held centre
stage on Thursday as athletes already arrived here
</P>
<P>
Hosts Indonesia, with the largest contingent, are favourites to
grab the most medals at the biennial games, which feature 34
events ranging from sports like soccer, swimming and athletics to
more exotic regional specialities such as sepak takraw, wushu and
traditional boat racing.
</P>
<P>
In the days leading up to the opening ceremony, athletes and
officials were making typical pre-games complaints about
unfinished or sub-par venues and housing facilities.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's badminton and shooting teams complained about an
infestation of mosquitoes at the main sports centre.
</P>
<P>
SEA Games officials apologised for hoisting an incorrect
Malaysian flag at the Hotel Mulia where many of the foreign
athletes are staying.
</P>
<P>
Thailand, who had a record-breaking haul of gold medals at
the 1995 Chiang Mai games, complained that their athletes had
been split up and housed in more than a dozen different hotels.
</P>
<P>
The smog, caused by raging forest fires in parts of
Indonesia, has not yet been a major problem in the Indonesian
capital but most team officials were taking precautions.
</P>
<P>
Many athletes have expressed concern about the smog and
whether it would affect their performances.
</P>
<P>
Officials from many teams said they were bringing face
masks and eye and nose drops to combat effects of the smog.
</P>
<P>
Some teams, such as Singapore's soccer squad, have already
encountered the smog in their training sessions in their home
countries.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian fans and supporters from neighbouring countries
are expected to be out in full force for the weeklong SEA
Games. A school holiday declared in Jakarta from October 13
through 18 will probably add to the crowds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
