<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Aids S. Africa in Low Income Housing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The United States has
granted South Africa 200 million Rand (about 43 million U.S.
dollars) in aid to meet the latter's development, local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The agreement to the effect was signed by South African Deputy
Finance Minister Gill Marcus and U.S. Ambassador James Joseph.
</P>
<P>
The American aid was mainly targeted at the South African
priorities such as low income housing, disadvantaged
universities, health care and the justice system, Marcus said.
</P>
<P>
Since 1985, the U.S. had given more than 4.6 billion Rand
(almost one billion U.S. dollars) in aid to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
In the early years most of this money went to non-governmental
organizations (NGO), but today it was almost evenly split between
NGO's and government, the report said.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last December the value of U.S fixed investment
in South Africa was eight billion U.S. Dollars. American firms
operating in South Africa had sales of about 10 billion dollars
and the value of bilateral trade last year was more than five
billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
