<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 08:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran to Suit Dutch Shipping Company for Unlawful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Iran announced today that its
judicial branch will take legal action against a Dutch liner owned
by Smit Tug Company for its unlawful activities in Iranian
waters.
</P>
<P>
Iran's official news agency IRNA quoted a statement of Mahmoud
Mohammadi, spokesman of the Foreign Ministry, as saying that the
judicial branch is investigating the case.
</P>
<P>
On august 19, the two Dutch vessels, contracted by Iran to
salvage a sunken Croatian ship in the Persian Gulf, abandoned the
mission and headed for another part of the Persian Gulf to pull
out the debris of a U.S. helicopter crashed in Iran's territorial
waters.
</P>
<P>
Iran announced in September that two Dutch vessels were
confiscated by the Iranian security guards at Imam Khomeini port
for operating in Iran's territorial waters without permission.
</P>
<P>
In the statement today, the Foreign Ministry spokesman said
that all the shipping crews with the exception of the captains in
addition to some flotillas had been released against the guarantee
provided by the company.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi said that the Dutch ships were seized at the time
when they were engaged in a different kind of activity other than
the assigned mission in the Iranian territorial waters.
</P>
<P>
"Such a measure was against the national security of the
Islamic Republic of Iran," the spokesman noted.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Dutch special delegation comprising a
Foreign Ministry official and the director of Smit International
Sea Contract arrived here on September 20, 1997 to negotiate with
the Iranian side.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman stated that the Dutch delegation was informed by
the Iranian officials during several sessions of the negotiation
that the act of abandoning their contracted assignment was unlawful
according to the international law and the terms of contract.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi noted that any plying of a foreign vessel within
Iran's territorial waters needed official permission from the
related Iranian agencies.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the Dutch delegation rendered its
apology for that operation and promised to compensate for all of
damages incurred Iran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
