<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Elderly In China Eager To Learn More </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Wang Xianfa, an 80-year-old
who was formerly in charge of the Henan provincial health
department in central China, decided to enroll in a local college
for senior citizens when he retired, and he's not the only one to
go to college after retirement.
</P>
<P>
Many of the elderly in Henan who want to add a little color to
their lives are taking courses in health care, psychology,
literature, history, calligraphy, photography, and painting in
local schools for senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
The first university for retired cadres was set up in Henan in
1985, but there are now 862 of these schools, with more than
600,000 students.
</P>
<P>
"The more exercise the brain gets, the sharper it becomes,"
Wang, who used to be a doctor, explains. His daily life also
includes reciting poems, both in school and after class.
</P>
<P>
Another senior citizen, Lu Zhaoya, has had his paintings and
calligraphies at more than 70 exhibitions both at home and abroad,
and has won at least 30 prizes. Recently, a book of photos of his
paintings was published.
</P>
<P>
In the first national calligraphy and painting contest for the
elderly held earlier this year, a dozen contestants from Henen
were given awards.
</P>
<P>
And, while schools for the elderly in urban areas tend to focus
on courses that help one's cultural attainments, those in rural
areas usually hold courses on farming techniques like planting
crops and breeding livestock. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
