<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- In their book "L'Affaire Yann Piat," journalists Andre
Rougeot and Jean-Michel Verne developed the hypothesis of a plot
by secret agents of the state who killed parliament deputy Piat,
because of his knowledge about real estate projects linking the
mafia with two government ministers at that time.
</P>
<P>
Francois Leotard, who was defense minister at that time, and
the mayor of Marseille Jean-Claude Gaudin, who were suggested in
the book as the men behind the murder, had warned the authors of
the book that they would counter-attack.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- Former Defense Minister and president of the Union for
French Democracy, Francois Leotard, and the mayor of Marseille
Jean-Claude Gaudin have launched a legal proceeding against the
book "L'Affaire Yann Piat: Assassins au Coeur du Pouvoir," calling
for the suppression of certain pages of the book and urging its
authors to "immediately prove what they have presented."
</P>
<P>
But the authors of the book, journalists Jean-Michel Verne and
Andre Rougeot, said they had not hinted who were behind the murder
of Yann Piat, a parliament deputy assassinated in 1994. 
</P>
