<HEADLINE> Health Education Paying Off In Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, October 9 (Xinhua) -- A health education program is
paying off in northeast China's Liaoning Province, with the
average life expectancy increasing in just seven years by more
than half a year to 71.71.
</P>
<P>
According to local health officials, the infant mortality rate
has dropped by eight per thousand compared since 1990 and the
incidence of epidemics is down 20 percent and the mortality rate
down by two thirds.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning has stepped up health education since 1990 and has
established a health education network in 14 cities, 26,540 rural
villages and 10 million families, with different fitness programs
and training courses targeting different groups of people.
</P>
<P>
Eighty percent of primary and middle schools in the province
have health education courses that have helped greatly in reducing
the incidence of diseases that affect the young.
</P>
<P>
A recent study of 3,000 students in 30 primary schools found
that the ratio near-sighted students has dropped to 18 percent
from 21 percent and the incidence of trachoma is now 9 percent
compared with 17 percent in 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
