<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Homa Bay Blocked by Water Hyacinth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's Homa Bay has been
blocked following the spread of water hyacinth to the area, the
Daily Nation reported today.
</P>
<P>
For the past three weeks, there has been no lake transport to
Homa Bay, even the large big steamer failed to pass through the
weed mass to dock at the Homa Bay pier, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya Railways authorities has sent out circulars to its
customers warning them not to deliver cargo destined for the area
and its environs for fear of the goods getting stuck in the water
hyacinth.
</P>
<P>
The authorities noted that "we have already sent a notice to
all our customers not to send cargo to Kisumu because the water
hyacinth has blocked a large part of Homa Bay, K'owuor and Kendu
Bay, which are the major docking stations in the local lake
transport."
</P>
<P>
However, the authorities said that the main routes including
Kisumu-Mwanza in Tanzania and Kisumu-Port Bell in Uganda are not
affected by the weed problem.
</P>
<P>
It pointed out that water hyacinth had not affected the ports
in Uganda and Tanzania to an extent that the ships cannot dock as
the steamers plying the main routes are powerful enough to easily
penetrate the weed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
