<HEADLINE> Iran Urges Pakistan to Punish Murderers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Supreme Leader Ali
Khamenei has put more pressure on the Pakistani government for it
to ferret and punish killers of five Iranians in the country last
month.
</P>
<P>
According to the Iran News today, Khamenei, while receiving
relatives of the murdered Iranians, said "This incident must be
seriously followed up by the Pakistani government and those who
have committed this crime must be brought to justice."
</P>
<P>
If Islamabad fails to fulfill its responsibility, the supreme
leader was quoted as saying, it would mean this government is
trying to assist the terrorists and would consequently cause
strain in the bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Five Iranian air force technicians of the Islamic Revolutionary
Guards Corps were killed on September 17 in Rawalpindi, near the
Pakistani capital of Islamabad. No one has claimed responsibility
for the attack.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the Shiite Muslim-dominant Iran and Sunni
Muslim-dominant Pakistan have more often than not been off-key
despite efforts to closing the ranks between them.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei expressed sorrow that the "dearest and best Iranian
youths could not enjoy a secure life" in a "friendly and
neighborly country like Pakistan."
</P>
<P>
"The criminal designs were fomented by those who are against
seeing the growth of a friendly relationship between the two
nations," he asseted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
