<DOCNO> XIE19971009.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africans Want Parliament to Remain in Cape </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The majority of South
Africans were in favor of retaining their parliament in Cape Town
rather than moving it to another place, South African Press
Association quoted research survey figures as showing.
</P>
<P>
At present, South Africa has three capital cities: Pretoria
(executive), Cape Town (legislative) and Bloemfontein (judicial).
</P>
<P>
There were proposals that parliament be moved to Pretoria to
save time and money as government officials and parliament
members involved now have to shuttle between these cities.
</P>
<P>
Surveys conducted in September to study public opinion on the
matter showed that 55 percent of the respondents said they wanted
parliament to stay in Cape Town, 17 percent felt that it should
be moved to Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
Six percent mentioned Midrand, a small city between Pretoria
and Johannesburg, and 4 percent were in favor of Bloemfontein.
Sixteen percent said they did not think much about the issue and
failed to mention any place.
</P>
<P>
When looking at the results in more detail, it revealed that
65 percent of whites compared to 50 percent of blacks chose Cape
Town as a suitable place for parliament.
</P>
<P>
Of the black respondents, 20 percent chose Pretoria compared
to 10 percent of whites.
</P>
<P>
Capetonians were more assertive on the matter. Some 74 percent
of whites and 89 percent of blacks surveyed did not want
parliament to be relocated.
</P>
<P>
Researchers said 2,000 people were interviewed in major
metropolitan areas across the country, highly representative of
the urban population in terms of age and income.
</P>
<P>
According to independent assessment, moving parliament from
Cape Town to Pretoria could cost 3.5 billion Rand (745 million
U.S. Dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
