<HEADLINE> Kenyan Bank Head Honored Africa's Best Banker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of Kenya (CBK)
Governor Micah Cheserem has been honored the "African Central
Banker of the Year" by the "Euromoney Magazine".
</P>
<P>
The September issue of the magazine said that Cheserem's work
over the last five years had helped to stabilize the Kenyan
economy in the face of great difficulties.
</P>
<P>
He has made significant contributions to Kenyan economy and
has managed to tame inflation rate to well below the 9 percent
mark from 101 percent recorded in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The governor is one among a "handful of people to have come
out of the IMF (International Monetary Fund)-Kenya tussle with
any credit", it noted.
</P>
<P>
The magazine described Cheserem as a reformer who has voiced
disapproval at the hardliners' refusal to co-operate with the
IMF.
</P>
<P>
Despite the recent political upheaval and a lurching Shilling,
the governor has done an admirable job, said the magazine, adding
that he had been eager to discuss a shadow program with the IMF
which would provide advice but no credits.
</P>
<P>
Cheserem's award was motivated by his recent moves to team up
with the Minister for Finance, Musalia Mudavadi, to renew talks
with the IMF, it added.
</P>
<P>
The magazine has declared South Africa's Trevor Manuel as the
Best African Finance Minister of the year as he is said to have
put macro-reform into the right gear.
</P>
<P>
"Euromoney Magazine" has annual awards for top finance
minister and central banker worldwide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
