<HEADLINE> Israel's Industrial Output Growth Rate Slows Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The growth rate of Israel's
industrial output slacked up to only 2.4 percent in the
January-July period, Israeli Manufacturers Association said today.
</P>
<P>
The figure indicates there will be a 3 percent growth for the
whole year, the lowest in seven years, said Shuki Abramowitz, head
of the association's economics division.
</P>
<P>
According to a study the association conducted, the machinery
and equipment sector reported a slowdown of 6.3 percent in the
first six months of the year, whereas the textiles industry
experienced a 3.4 percent slowdown.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile the rubber sand plastics sector had a 1.4 slowdown
and the non-metallic minerals industry slowed by 1.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
In contrast with these figures, the electronics components
sector reported a growth of 10.8 percent, while the
telecommunications equipment grew by 10.5 percent and the metals
industry grew by 5.1 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
