<HEADLINE> Rural Chinese Women Asking for More Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Ying Zhulan, of Yongding
village of Wenling city in east China's Zhejiang province, has
made a name for herself as a farmer technician.
</P>
<P>
Ying, who is in her 30s, did this by acquiring fruit growing
skills two years ago and has become a village role model by
striking it rich using new farming technology. All this with two
ha. of citrus trees and 1.7 ha. of watermelons.
</P>
<P>
Women villagers are now eager to know more about new farming
techniques, and more than 60,000 of them in the province have
received special training, and 14,000 have become peasant
technicians in the past three years.
</P>
<P>
The local government began the training program in 1994 to help
them get away from poverty, and rural women have become the
backbone of farm work as more men began to go outside the province
to make money after China's opening-up began, an official of the
Zhejiang Women's Federation explains.
</P>
<P>
Women account for more than 60 percent of the province's farm
laborers, so any increase in their knowledge of science and
technology helps local agricultural development, the official
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
