<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Agency Aids Uganda Against Cassava Mosaic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The United States Agency for
International Development (USAID) has offered over one million
U.S. Dollars for rapid multiplication of mosaic resistant cassava
varieties in Uganda.
</P>
<P>
According to local daily, The New Vision today, this comes in
the wake of over 60 million dollars per year lost due to the
disease. Most of the districts in Uganda lost their yield.
</P>
<P>
Officials in charge of the project were quoted as saying that
the project will replace the affected cassava and transform
cassava to an export cash crop.
</P>
<P>
The project funded by USAID from the PL-480 Food Security Fund
will be jointly implemented by the International Institute of
Tropical Agriculture and Ugandan National Agriculture Research
Organization.
</P>
<P>
The project will run over a four year period from this year.
Over ten million cuttings will be available for multiplication
farmers.
</P>
<P>
About 60,000 hectares of cassava equivalent to 600,000 tons
valuing 60 million dollars is lost each year to the mosaic in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's annual output of cassava, a staple food in recent
years is about 3.93 million tons.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971009.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Digital to End Zimbabwe's Phone Waiting Line </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Posts and
Telecommunications Corporation (PTC) is targeting to wipe out the
telephone waiting list within the next four years and thereafter
manage to connect new customers within days.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Information, Posts and Telecommunications Chen
Chimutengwende told parliament Wednesday that the digitalization
program being undertaken in stages had been introduced to improve
distribution of telephone services countryside.
</P>
<P>
"The country's total digital exchange capacity is now 48
percent of the whole network and it is expected to reach 80
percent by the year 2000. Transmission capacity is also expected
to reach 70 percent in two years time," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
If the same rate was maintained, he said, the PTC would be
able to wipe out the waiting list of over 100,000 by the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
He said Zimbabwe, with a population of 12 million, now had
212,000 telephone lines compared to 98,376 main lines at
independence in 1980.
</P>
<P>
He said in achieving this, the PTC had to tackle the problems
of satisfying a growing demand for telephones, replacing an old
telephone system which had outlived its life span and expanding
the network to cover areas which were previously ignored.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
