<HEADLINE> Urbanites in Guangzhou Spend More on Cultural Activities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Fang Sheng, young deputy chief
editor of a newspaper in Guangzhou, capital of south China's
Guangdong province, spends a quarter of his income just on tennis
and badminton, which he plays at least twice a week.
</P>
<P>
This has showed the fact that now the residents in this
moderately developed city are spending more on their cultural
activities.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey showed that per capita cost of recreation and
education in the city was 976 yuan (about 122 US dollars) last
year, 2.5 times the amount four years ago. And culture used up
12.1 percent of the amount spent on living in 1996, compared with
8.1 percent in 1992.
</P>
<P>
People's income goes increasingly to TV, music, sports
activities, and travel, and education costs grew 72 percent in the
past four years.
</P>
<P>
The survey also showed that the expenditure on cultural
activities in the city in 1996 ranked first among China's ten
largest cities, surpassing Shanghai by 198 yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
