<HEADLINE> Female Chef Sets Noodle Pulling Record in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 9 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese chef has made 3,000
meters of noodles drawing the dough out by hand, according to a
report in the Beijing Evening News.
</P>
<P>
Hu Shuxia's masterpiece beat out five other contestants at a
"Noodle Pulling" contest organized by China's largest TV network,
China Central Television.
</P>
<P>
The contestants, who were from different parts of the country
had to draw a kilogram of dough into noodles as thin as nylon
thread.
</P>
<P>
Hu is a chef at the Wuyi Hotel in Xi'an city. Her noodles were
all connected and were measured at a total length of 2,940.48
meters. The "noodle thread" was long enough to go around Beijing's
Tian'anmen Square, the world's largest square.
</P>
<P>
Hand-pulled noodles have been a favorite on Chinese dining
tables for centuries, even though the large variety of
machine-made noodles available today provide urbanities with
greater convenience.
</P>
<P>
Noodles are an important part of various celebrations like
birthday parties, in addition to blowing out candles and sharing
cakes, because many people still believe that long noodles signify
longevity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
