<DOCNO> XIE19971009.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Coach Calls For More Matches for Young Divers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese divers should take
part in more formal competitions in order to steel their nerves, a
famous diving coach recommended here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Hu Enyong, coach of the Olympic silver medalist Yu Zhuocheng,
said that it's a right time for the Chinese divers to bid farewell
to the current close-door training system.
</P>
<P>
"Under the existing system, many divers usually have top-notch
performances in the training but lose their forms in the official
competitions. This is an abnormal phenomenon," Hu said after the
men's one-meter diving finals of the eighth Chinese National Games
to be officially opened on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Guo Jingjing of Hebei province happened to justify Hu's
worrysome argument.
</P>
<P>
Guo, tipped as "the precious successor to the triple Olympic
champion Fu Mingxia", failed to qualify for the women's 10-meter
platform finals.
</P>
<P>
The bad omen also beckoned on anothr promising budding star Cai
Yuyan, Hu said. Cai led the semifinals in the women's platform but
slipped to the sixth at last.
</P>
<P>
"Cai surprised everyone including herself to lead the semis,
but she told me she was too nervous on the platform to remember
anything in the finals," Hu lamented.
</P>
<P>
"Cai had the calibre to win the title after half-a-year's hard
training, the only thing she lacks is the experience of major
competitions both at home and abroad."
</P>
<P>
Other experts, including Beijing coach Wu Guolin and
international judge Xuan Zengyong also echoed the same argument,
saying that the lack of experience has blunted some Chinese
divers, especially those youngsters, to achieve satisfactory
results in the international diving arenas.
</P>
<P>
"Divers in some Western countries begin their competitions at a
very young age, usually twice a week. But our young stars cannot
see a major event in one whole year. Thus, it's not a surprise
for them to make fatal mistakes in their eventual formal
competitions," Wu said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
