<HEADLINE> Peso Plunge Temporary: Philippine Business Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Business leaders in the
Philippines believed that the peso's depreciation was temporary
and the country would weather the financial storm, the Philippine
News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The business leaders expressed their optimism when attending
the 23rd Philippine Business Conference which opened in Cebu City
Wednesday. President Fidel Ramos would address the meeting Friday.
</P>
<P>
Trade and Industry Secretary Cesar Bautista said at the meeting
that the country is not experiencing "a foreign exchange crisis",
but only a "wide-spreading storm", citing as proof the country's
reserves, high export growth rate and low-level inflation.
</P>
<P>
"The difficulties that arose were not the result of any
intrinsic weakness in our own economy. They were the consequence
of a general realignment of regional currencies brought about by
the financial meltdown in Thailand," he said.
</P>
<P>
Bautista encouraged the business leaders to help lessen the
adverse effects of the peso's devaluation by increasing
productivity, bringing down production cost and accepting thinner
profit margins.
</P>
<P>
Federico Pascual, president of the Philippine Chamber of
Commerce and Industry, shared the view with Bautista, saying while
the banking and real property sectors remained sound, the
country's export growth rate of 22 percent is the highest in
Southeast Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
