<HEADLINE> NATO Begins War Game in Romania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) today started a war game at a Romanian
military base in Constanta, on the coast of the Black Sea.
</P>
<P>
The entire game on marine logistic support for peacekeeping
operations was to be carried out on paper, and was the first of
such kind of simulation held outside the NATO 16 member nations.
</P>
<P>
Joining the game, code-named Cooperative Support '97, were nine
countries from the Western military bloc and an equal number of
members of NATO's Partnership for Peace program from East Europe.
</P>
<P>
The participating East European nations, who committed their
military forces to the game, were Albania, Bulgaria, Estonia,
Macedonia, Georgia, Lithuania, Poland, Romania and Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman with NATO's military command told the ROMPRES news
agency today that the war game is not only of extreme importance
for NATO, but also for the alliance's East European partners.
</P>
<P>
The game is scheduled to end on October 15. 
</P>
