<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Welcomes U.S. Ban Against Tamil Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka said today that the
U.S. decision to ban the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE)
from entering or raising fund in the United States was a victory
of Sri Lanka's foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokesman Ravinatha Aryasinha said this
morning at a news conference that the U.S. decision was a
testimony of a strong and healthy bilateral relationship between
Sri Lanka and the U.S.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madelene Albright Wednesday announced
that the LTTE, along with 29 other organizations in the world, was
on the terrorist organization list and would be barred from
entering and raising fund in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
She said members of the listed groups would be ineligible for
visas to enter the U.S. and that their funds would be frozen under
a new anti-terrorism law signed by American President Bill Clinton
in April 1996.
</P>
<P>
Aryasinha said Sri Lanka's Foreign Minister Lakshman
Kadirgamar, who concluded a visit to the U.S. Wednesday night, was
informed by the U.S. State Department of the decision hours before
leaving Washington.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister had stressed Sri Lanka's request to the
U.S. to declare the LTTE as a terrorist organization while meeting
with Albright, Aryasinha said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said: "This decision by the government of the
United States can be expected to have a considerable effect on how
other governments and international organizations view the LTTE."
</P>
<P>
The LTTE has been fighting for an independent state in the
north and east of this island nation since 1983. So far 55,000
people had died of the war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
