<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Exporters Worry over Peso Depreciation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- While government planners
remained optimistic that the fall of the peso will advance
exports, exporters themselves are not too happy about the 35
percent plunge of the peso.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine News Agency today quoted export leader Benson
Dakay as saying that exporters whose products are manufactured
mostly from imported raw materials are the most adversely
affected.
</P>
<P>
These products include semiconductor devices, communication
equipment, electronic products, garments and even furniture, all
top dollar earners in the country, Dakay said.
</P>
<P>
Exporters who manufacture products with high local content are
also expected to feel the pinch of the weak peso because of the
rise in production and transport costs, he said.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the exporters had already been burdened by the
liquidity crunch which has jacked up interest rates and restricted
businessmen's access to credit, he added.
</P>
<P>
The peso has depreciated from 26.2 pesos per dollar to the
current all-time low of 35.56 pesos to one dollar since the
currency turmoil swept Southeast Asia in early July.
</P>
<P>
Dakay said the exporters favor an exchange rate of one dollar
to 30 pesos and consider a rate beyond this level would hurt the
export sector.
</P>
<P>
They also hope the government will be able to keep the
inflation and interest rates at manageable levels to allow the
export sector to advance, he said.
</P>
<P>
The country's export sector grew by an average of 22 percent in
the first eight months this year, the highest growth rate in
Southeast Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971009.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
