<HEADLINE> Malaysia Hopes to Host World Meeting on Regulating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia hopes to play host
to a world meeting here as soon as possible to study its proposal
for prudential regulations for currency trading, particularly in
relation to hedge trading, Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad said
today.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has asked for a Malaysian to be seconded to the
organization to assist it in looking into ways to regulate
currency trading, Mahathir told reporters after presenting a
keynote address at a seminar on "Strategic Thinking -- Lessons
From Three Great Asian Civilizations For Today's Modern
Management" here.
</P>
<P>
He said that an officer has already been identified to be
seconded to the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said that when he was in Hong Kong recently, the heads
of the World Bank, the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the
World Trade Organization (WTO) were supportive of Malaysia's
proposal.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia made the proposal following unwarranted speculative
and manipulative attacks on ASEAN currencies starting with the
Thai Baht in early July which adversely affected their economies.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said that even last night, WTO director-general Renato
Ruggiero phoned his deputy, Anwar Ibrahim, who is also Finance
Minister, informing him of the trade body's support for Malaysia
to initiate controls on currency trading.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in his keynote address at the one-day seminar, he said
that his government is formulating a strategy which is expected to
successfully deal with the effects of the fall of the Ringgit with
the full cooperation of all Malaysians.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir did not elaborate on the strategy but gave an
assurance that it would not be detrimental to any party.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Cabinet, at its weekly meeting yesterday,
discussed several strategies but the people's full support and
discipline were required to deal with the problem.
</P>
<P>
"We are indulging in strategic thinking at the moment. We may
come up with a solution soon. Give the solution a chance and we
will overcome," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
