<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Ocean Port Conference to Be Held in Mumbai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 9 (Xinhua) -- A five-day conference of the
Indian Ocean region is scheduled to be held in Mumbai (Bombay),
India, from October 13 to chalk out a regional memorandum of
understanding (MOU) for port state control, official sources said
here today.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is part of a move to keep ports free of polluting
ships and to take necessary action against substandard vessels.
The conference, which will be attended by 21 countries, will draw
up norms to be followed by them to check ships from polluting the
ports of member countries.
</P>
<P>
New norms will enable extended control of the ships in regional
waters, harmonized system of surveys and inspections, and
avoidance of unfair competition between ports in the region, the
same sources said.
</P>
<P>
The MOU will have common criteria for inspections, harmonized
inspections and education procedures, internationally approved
qualification of control officers and an internationally agreed
code of conduct.  
</P>
</TEXT>
