<HEADLINE> WB Aids Indonesia's Solar Power Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank and U.N. global
environmental facilities (GEF) have granted a financial assistance
worth 40 million US dollars for Indonesia's solar power plant
projects in rural areas, an official said.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Head for Technological Development Affairs of the Agency
for Assessment and Application of Technology (BPPT) Haryono
Djojodihardjo said here last night the construction of the solar
power plants, located in West Java, South Sulawesi and Lampung
provinces, began last October 1.
</P>
<P>
Of the 40 million US dollars, 20 million dollars was obtained
from World Bank soft loan while the rest from GEF, Antara news
agency today quoted Haryono as saying.
</P>
<P>
BPPT plans to build 200,000 solar power plant units all over
the country. Each unit is said to cost 450 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Australian government has also provided similar assistance
for villages in the Indonesian eastern region, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
