<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Castro Insists Cuban Exiles Were Behind Hotel Bombs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Cuba's President Fidel Castro
insisted today that a Miami-based Cuban exile group, the Cuban
American National Foundation (CANF), organized a series of small
bomb attacks at hotels in Havana over the last five months.
</P>
<P>
"All these explosions were organized by the Cuban-American
Foundation and we know enough about this and we are absolutely
sure and we can categorically affirm it, there is no doubt,"
Castro, quoted by the Cuban news agency Prensa Latina, said.
</P>
<P>
Castro was speaking at the opening of the Communist Party's
Fifth Party Congress in Havana. His address was a seven-hour
review of Cuba's economic and political policy in recent years.
</P>
<P>
At least seven small bombs exploded at Cuban tourist hotels and
a restaurant in the four months up to September, and two others
exploded abroad at Cuban tourist offices in Nassua and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
One of the bombs at a Havana hotel on September 4 killed an
Italian businessman and all of the explosions caused slight damage.
</P>
<P>
Cuban authorities in September detained Salvadorean Raul
Ernesto Cruz Leon on charges he planted six of the bombs and said
the CANF was behind the attacks. But the CANF, a powerful
anti-government group, denied the charge saying it had nothing to
do with the bombs.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Castro referred to 20 cases of sabotage aimed at
the tourist industry and charged that all of them were "organized
and supplied" from the United States. He reiterated Cuba's demand
that Washington act to stop such attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
