<DOCNO> XIE19971009.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Make Feasibility Study of Ganges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The feasibility study of the
much-talked Ganges Barrage is likely to start early next year,
said the sources from the Bangladeshi Ministry of Water Resources
Ministry here today.
</P>
<P>
The proposed Ganges Barrage will cost 8 billion U.S. dollars,
according to a preliminary estimate.
</P>
<P>
The project proposal for the feasibility study at a cost of 630
million taka (about 14.19 million dollars) has already finalized.
</P>
<P>
Donor countries and agencies including Japan, Netherlands, ADB
(the Asian Development Bank) and other countries of the European
Union have agreed to finance the study, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The feasibility study would be completed in phases within three
years.
</P>
<P>
The signing of agreements with the funding countries and the
donor agencies regarding the funding of the feasibility study
would be completed by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The local component of the total cost of the feasibility study
has been fixed at 45 million taka (about 1.01 million dollars).
The remaining amount of 585 million taka (about 13.18 dollars)
will be funded by the donors, the sources stated.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of the study will be on social, environmental
and economic implication of the Ganges Barrage. After completion
of the first phase, the second phase, the detailed technical
aspect of the barrage, will start.
</P>
<P>
The Ganges Barrage has become an urgent necessity to save at
least 40 million people living in the south and southwestern parts
of the country from impending social and economic disaster.
</P>
<P>
"After the construction of the Farakka Barrage by India, the
social and economic lives of the people in this part of the
country have been facing a total disaster," a Water Resources
Ministry official said, adding that construction of the Ganges
Barrage could save the area.
</P>
<P>
The official said the Farakka barrage is largely responsible
for the increasing level of salinity in the area. It has damaged
the soil fertility of the area, and it has also been destroying
the Sundarbans, the world's biggest mangrove forest.
</P>
<P>
The Ganges Barrage will be constructed at Pangsha of Rajbari
district. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971009.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali New Government Wins Vote of Confidence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Nepal's new Prime Minister
Surya Bahadur Thapa won a vote of confidence in the Lower House
Thursday, three days after he took over as head of a new coalition
government.
</P>
<P>
Thapa, president of the National Democratic Party (RPP),
secured 109 votes in the 205-seat Lower House, six more than the
minimum needed to govern the country, Speaker of the Lower House
Ram Chandra Poudel announced.
</P>
<P>
MPs of the Communist Party of Nepal (United Marxist-Leninist,
CPN-UML), the ruling partner of the Chand-led coalition government
which was toppled on October 4 by a no-confidence motion tabled by
the Nepali Congress (NC), boycotted the vote.
</P>
<P>
As Thursday is the eighth day of Dashain, the biggest festival
in Nepal, MPs from the CPN-UML asked the speaker of the Lower
House to postpone the vote till the festival is over.
</P>
<P>
But the speaker did not change his mind, saying the prime
minister had made a request that he be allowed to seek a vote of
confidence as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
RPP parliamentary party leader Lokendra Bahadur Chand, who was
voted out of power by the NC with the support of Thapa and his
followers, also boycotted the vote along with his two supporters.
</P>
<P>
Thapa's government, the sixth in Nepal since 1990, is currently
a coalition of RPP and the Nepal Sadbhavana Party, but the NC will
join later.
</P>
<P>
His government must obtain a vote of confidence in the Lower
House within 30 days.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971009.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Analysts Differ on Indonesia's Plan for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government's plan
to seek long-term loans from international financial institutions,
including the International Monetary Fund (IMF), to help overcome
the current financial crisis has drawn mixed reactions from
economists and analysts here.
</P>
<P>
Most of economists and analysts hailed the government's plan
announced Wednesday, saying the decision was the best alternative
in view of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
"There is no other choice but to seek IMF help. It's a matter
of survival," head of the Indonesian Business Data Center
Christianto said last night.
</P>
<P>
The crisis, if not dealt with properly and quickly, could lead
to political instability, affecting the convening of the People's
Consultative Assembly next March to elect president and vice
president of the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
President Soeharto endorsed a decision Wednesday to seek
outside help, including from the IMF, to restore confidence in the
battered Indonesian rupiah (the national currency).
</P>
<P>
But no details were given on how much assistance would be
sought or in what form.
</P>
<P>
But analysts said any package would be far less than the 17.2
billion US dollars received by Thailand, the first Southeast Asian
nation to turn to multilateral agencies after its currency was
browbeaten.
</P>
<P>
Despite several measures adopted by the government to prevent
further depreciation of the rupiah against the US dollar since mid
July, the value of the Indonesian currency has continued to
weaken.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah has fallen about 55 percent against the dollar since
the beginning of this year following offshore speculative attacks
on the currency and a rush by local companies to hedge their
foreign borrowings.
</P>
<P>
Economist Raden Pardede said the government's latest move would
help restore confidence, especially among local companies which
had rushed for the US dollar over the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
Officials here attributed the persistent weakening of the
rupiah over the past few weeks to the increasing demand by local
corporations to purchase dollars to refinance their dollar debts.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's Chamber of Commerce and Industry Chairman for the
Middle East Committee Sudradjat welcomed the plan, saying
long-term loans from international institutions will allow the
government to intervene in the market, so that the rupiah may
reach its reasonable exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Rino A. Effendi, chief economist at Danareksa
Securities, said that the move should be accompanied by total
economic reformation involving sectors such as banking and
property.
</P>
<P>
"The question in people's mind now is why our economy is so
sensitive to interest rates and currency fluctuation. That means
there is something wrong with our economy. Therefore, economic
reforms in banking and property sectors as well as other sectors
have to be pursued," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, the independent economic think tank Econit criticized
the move, saying Indonesia's economic condition does not warrant
IMF and World Bank intervention.
</P>
<P>
"The present currency crisis is still manageable and
Indonesia's economy is not yet in a critical condition," Econit
Director Rizal Ramli said.
</P>
<P>
He also warned of the adverse consequences of seeking IMF and
World Bank assistance, such as a sharp fall in economic growth,
declining purchasing power and an increasing number of poor
people.
</P>
<P>
Noted economist Anwar Nasution, meanwhile, said the government
must clarify the form of IMF and World Bank assistance so that the
package won't burden Indonesians in the future.
</P>
<P>
"If the assistance is in the form of funds, they will certainly
impose strict conditions and Indonesia will have to bow to
international financial institutions' pressure," he added.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the World Bank's representative in Jakarta
Dennis de Tray said Wednesday any assistance given to Indonesia in
the wake of a currency crisis would be aimed at restoring
confidence rather than providing financial help.
</P>
<P>
"Indonesia is still quite well financed," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971009.0251 </DOCNO>
