<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prodi Meets President on Government crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi
discussed the government crises over the 1998 budget with
President Oscar Luige Scalfano Wednesday, sources said.
</P>
<P>
Prodi was expected to update Scalfano on the state of his
majority and the prospects of an agreement with the Communist
Refoundation party over the budget impasse that threatens to
topple the government.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the Senate Wednesday morning, Prodi renewed his
appeal to the left-wing party to support his government and the
25-trillion-lira budget.
</P>
<P>
A government crisis "would make it less likely for Italians to
get what they have a right to: a country led by an authoritative
and responsible government open to the future and respected by
everyone," Prodi said.
</P>
<P>
Communist Refoundation opposes the 1998 budget draft, seen by
the government as a key step toward consolidating Italy's effort
to clean up its state accounts and enter the single European
currency in 1999.
</P>
<P>
"We are now on an arduous and difficult journey," Prodi said,
"and we don't want a failure in carrying out the commitments we
have assumed and take Italy back to a time of continuously
changing coalitions and uncertain balances."
</P>
<P>
After Lower House debate Tuesday, the government fought off
attempts by the opposition to call a vote on the situation.
</P>
</TEXT>
