<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Earthquake Damage Greater Than Initial Estimate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Earthquakes have caused greater
damage to central Italy than initial estimates indicate,
said Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi today.
</P>
<P>
"We are still assessing the damage; we'll need a few more
days," said Prodi in addressing the senate on the budget crisis
that threatens his government.
</P>
<P>
He called on the parliament to pass "far-reaching" measures to
help the provinces of Umbria and Marches to recover from the
disaster.
</P>
<P>
The 1998 budget draft includes 800 billion lire (460 million
U.S. dollars) for emergency assistance and reconstruction. While
civil protection officials estimate the cost to repair the damage
at between 1.5 trillion lire (862.5 billion dollars) and 2
trillion lire (1.15 trillion dollars), not including damage to
artwork.
</P>
<P>
Earthquakes on September 26 and October 3 killed 12 people, and
left tens of thousands of people homeless. The earthquakes also
damaged the Basilica of St. Francis of Assisi and other cultural
treasures throughout the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
