<DOCNO> XIE19971009.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy, Saudis to Enhance Economic Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto
Dini said today Italy is ready to help Saudi Arabia branch out from
its traditional economic reliance on oil.
</P>
<P>
Dini said this as he opened a session of the joint
Italian-Saudi commission designed for closer trade ties between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Italy is prepared to place its knowhow in smaller industry at
the Saudis' disposal and to set up joint ventures and make direct
investments, Dini said.
</P>
<P>
The joint commission meeting, chaired by Dini and Saudi Finance
Minister Ibrahim Al Assaf, followed a series of high-level
contacts between the two countries and a visit to Saudi port city
of Jeddah by Dini and Italian President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro.
</P>
<P>
More than 40 Italian firms are operating in Saudi Arabia, which
is Italy's third biggest oil supplier, after Libya and Iran.
</P>
<P>
Through the work of the commission, the Saudi government
expects not only to diversify its economy, but also to accelerate
the privatization of its petrochemicals, telecommunications and
power sectors. Italy also has started or is planning major
sell-offs in these areas.
</P>
<P>
Trade between the two countries amounted to almost 3.5 billion
U.S. dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
Forty-four percent of Italian exports were engineering
products, 10 percent were chemicals and pharmaceuticals, while 80
percent of Saudi exports were crude oil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
