<HEADLINE> Seven Major Projects to Be Started Soon in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Seven major investment projects
worth over 2 billion U.S. dollars will be started soon in South
Sri Lanka, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The projects include an international sea port at Hambantota,
diversions of the Uma Oya River and the Menik Ganga River, an
international airport, a power plant, a highway, an electrified
railway and an oil refinery.
</P>
<P>
Eighty-four leading companies in the world will bid for these
projects.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan President Chandrika Kumaratunga on Wednesday met a
group of representatives from those foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
She said the incentive package already offered to foreign
investors has been described as the best in Asia.
</P>
<P>
She assured them that further concessions and incentives would
be provided for large-scale investments.
</P>
<P>
The president added that Southern province had many untapped
natural resources as well as an educated workforce which would
enable investors to run their projects smoothly and efficiently.
</P>
