<HEADLINE> Thailand to Urge Australia to Lift Chicken Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Thailand is expected to press
Australia to lift an eight-year-old ban on imports of Thai cooked
chicken when Australian Trade Minister Tim Fischer comes to
Bangkok later this week.
</P>
<P>
While Australia maintains that the problem is "purely
technical" and based "on hygiene," Thailand sees it as a trade
barrier, according to Thai officials.
</P>
<P>
Fischer, who is also a deputy prime minister, is due to visit
Thailand from Saturday to next Thursday, according to an
Australian embassy announcement available today.
</P>
<P>
Trade and investment will be highlighted in talks between
Fischer and Thai ministers.
</P>
<P>
Fischer is scheduled to meet Prime Minister Chavalit
Yongchaiyudh and hold separate talks with Deputy Prime Minister
Thaksin Shinawatra, Agriculture Minister Chucheep Hansawat and
Commerce Minister Narongchai Akrasanee.
</P>
<P>
The Australian minister may urge Thailand to reduce import
tariffs on Australian goods, including fruit, cheese, wine, dairy
products and electronic components.
</P>
<P>
Thailand exports computer components, canned food and frozen
seafood to Australia, while it imports gold and other minerals,
dairy products, cereals and machinery from Australia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971009.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Set to Push Social Insurance Across Country </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Encouraged by the success of a
series of experimental social insurance programs in the country,
China is set to greatly expand the coverage of social welfare
schemes across all domestic sectors, according to a spokesman for
the Ministry of Labor.
</P>
<P>
While focusing on pension, unemployment and medical insurance,
the State will also improve industrial accident insurance and
maternity insurance for women workers, said today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the institutes in charge of running these
social insurance programs are being asked to upgrade management
and improve service, said Dang Xiaojie, the spokesman for the
Ministry of Labor.
</P>
<P>
According to Dang, by the end of last year, more than 87
million workers, or 78 percent of the total work force, had joined
pension insurance schemes.
</P>
<P>
Last year, a total of 117.1 billion yuan (14 billion US
dollars) was collected in pension insurance, some 103.1 billion
yuan (12 billion dollars) was paid out.
</P>
<P>
Some 3.31 million people received unemployment payments last
year, an increase of 27 percent over the previous year. With the
help of this money, 1.87 million people were able to find new jobs
last year.
</P>
<P>
Over 31 million workers were covered by industrial accident
insurance last year, a growth of 18.66 percent over 1995's figure,
and the number of female workers taking out maternity insurance
increased by 34.35 percent, surpassing 20 million last year.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, more than 7.9 million workers were
covered by social medical insurance, an increase of 12.6 percent
over the 1995 figure.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
