<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, October 9 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. Senate Wednesday again failed to break a
Republican filibuster holding up action on a bill designed to
revise campaign finance rules.
</P>
<P>
That 52-47 vote was eight short of the 60 needed to end debate
and proceed with the measure. Majority Republicans declared it
dead after a nearly identical vote on the bill Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The main Somali factions Wednesday agreed to meet at
the Arab League (AL) headquarters in Cairo this month in a bid to
end the country's seven-year civil war, a senior AL official said.
</P>
<P>
The upcoming meeting aims to pave the way for a national
reconciliation conference slated for Bosaso, south of Somali
capital of Mogadishu, on November 1, said Samir Hosni, who is in
charge of the Somali file in the AL.
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian-American consultations started here Wednesday
to discuss a wide range of bilateral and international issues,
according to the Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
The consultations are conducted by First Deputy Secretary of
State Strobe Talbott, who is the head of an inter-departmental
delegation of the U.S. government, and the Russian side, whose
head is Deputy Foreign Minister Georgy Mamedov.
</P>
<P>
During the consultations the two sides will continue the
Russian-American dialogue, which was noticeably accelerated after
the latest session of the Gore-Chernomyrdin commission in Moscow,
and the talks of the Russian foreign minister in New York, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
OTTAWA -- Canada's wheat production is expected to drop 20.8
percent to 23.6 million tons this year due to reduced planted
acreage and lower yields.
</P>
<P>
Statistics Canada said Wednesday in its September production
estimates that of all the major crops surveyed, only canola,
soybeans and flaxseed were reported to show an increase in
production.
</P>
<P>
PYONGYANG -- Kim Jong Il, leader of the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK), Wednesday was formally named general
secretary of the Workers' Party of Korea (WPK).
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made by the WPK Central Committee and the
Military Commission of the WPK Central Committee in a "special
report."
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto Wednesday
expressed the hope that Kim Jong II's formal election as the
general secretary of the Workers' Party of Korea will help
improve relations between Japan and the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto told reporters at his official residence that he
expects bilateral negotiations at the level of deputy bureau chief
to head toward improvement, Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Foreign Minister Keizo Obuchi issued a statement,
saying that Japan cannot make immediate judgment if there will be
any change in DPRK's policies but will closely watch the situation.
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- The Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) and
South Korea Wednesday initialed an air control agreement, paving
the way to open an inter-Korean air route for commercial flights.
</P>
<P>
The arrangement came at the third round of inter-Korean
aviation meeting held in Bangkok, Thailand, under the auspices of
the International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO), said the
Ministry of Construction and Transportation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
