<HEADLINE> CPPCC Proposals Aid Beijing Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The motion put forward by 32
members of the Beijing Committee of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference (CPPCC) on the establishment of the
Wangfujing palaeoanthropological museum gave significant support
to the municipal leaders.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing government has now decided to set up the museum,
China Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
In December last year, remains confirmed as relics from the
Palaeolithic era some 22,000-25,000 years ago were discovered at
the construction site of the Oriental Square Plaza at the south
end of Wangfujing Street.
</P>
<P>
Motions such as the proposal to establish the museum have
played a significant role in helping the capital's governmental
organizations take appropriate decisions and improve their work.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, the CPPCC Beijing Committee has received 5,093
motions from its 740 members, up 13.5 percent over the previous
five-year period.
</P>
<P>
About 60 percent of the motions have been adopted by
governments at different levels, said committee official Shi
Weimin. Some motions have been of particular help to
decision-makers.
</P>
<P>
Eight committee members proposed a motion to strengthen
construction of Beijing's information infrastructure last
year. After the motion was delivered to the municipal government,
Mayor Jia Qinglin immediately decided to give priority to the
information infrastructure as a new aspect of the capital's
economic development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
