<HEADLINE> Russian PM Tries to Appease State Duma in Row Over Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin told the State Duma (lower house) today that it
should step back from confrontation with the government since new
economic policies are beginning to show results.
</P>
<P>
In a 30-minute speech, Chernomyrdin said foreign investment in
the first half of 1997 has reached 7 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Gross domestic product, the broadest measure of economic
health, has risen 0.2 percent in the first nine months of the year
against the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Industrial production has also risen 1.5 percent in the first
nine months, and he predicted the net grain harvest would be 84 to
85 million tons this year, up to 28 percent more than in the past
two years.
</P>
<P>
The State Duma, unsatisfied with the government's 1997 economic
and social policies, threatened to call for a no-confidence vote.
</P>
<P>
It also suggested the government bring revenue into state
coffers and suspend the preferential tax and customs policies for
some mainstay enterprises.
</P>
<P>
"I am convinced the country and the Russian people do not need
the vote or new elections," the prime minister said. 
</P>
