<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senior NATO Officer in Spain for Command Structure Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, October 8 (Xinhua) -- NATO's Supreme Allied Commander
in Europe, Wesley Clark, today urged Spain and Britain to reach
agreement on settling their dispute over Gibralta to facilitate
the reform of NATO command structure.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters in Madrid, Clark said that the reform of
NATO command structure is imperative and that the dispute between
Spain and Britain over Gibraltar is totally a bilateral issue
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The dispute between Spain and Britain over Gibraltar, a rocky
peninsula at the southern tip of Spain that dominates the western
entrance to the Mediterranean, has posed to be a major obstacle
against the reform of NATO command structure.
</P>
<P>
Gibraltar was ruled by Spain in the mid-15th century and merged
into Spanish territory in 1501. In 1704, Austria captured
Gilbraltar with the joining of Britain and the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Under the Treaty of Utrecht in 1713, Gibraltar formally became
a British colony, but Spain has claimed it ever since, generating
regular tensions with Britain.
</P>
<P>
Spanish Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar has expressed his hope
that Spain would join NATO's military command later this year, but
he admitted there would be some hurdles to be overcome first.
</P>
<P>
In London, the British government has threatened to block
Spain's full integration into NATO command structure unless
British military aircraft are allowed to make full use of the
airport on the contested British colony of Gibraltar.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Clark, who is a U.S. army general, said
that Spain is experienced in settling regional issues and that the
country should make great contribution in a new NATO command
structure.
</P>
<P>
He said that NATO is discussing the establishment a regional
command in Spain.
</P>
<P>
Clark arrived in Spain Tuesday on the mission to discuss with
the Spanish military the process of Spain's integration into NATO
command structure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971009.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Tourism Increasing in Peru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- More than 533,000 foreign tourists
visited Peru over the past nine months, a figure 9 percent higher
than the same period last year. The Ministry of Industry, Tourism
and Integration said today.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 12 months (October 1996 to September 1997),
706,000 people from abroad visited Peru. Peru officials believe
the number of foreign tourists this year could go as high as
750,000.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Reserves Central Bank of Peru said foreign
tourists spent 325 million U.S. dollars during the first semester
of this year, 12.1 percent higher than the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Tourism is the third highest foreign currency generator for
Peru. For the first seven months of this year, the average tourist
spent about 977.5 dollars during his or her stay in this South
American country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
