<HEADLINE> Nicaragua, Honduras Sign Accord Against Timber Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Nicaragua and Honduras have
signed an accord to fight timber smuggling along their borders,
sources from the Nicaraguan government said today.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed on Tuesday in Managua by the
Nicaraguan Ministry of Environment and National Resources and the
Honduran Ministry of Environment.
</P>
<P>
Nicaraguan and Honduran authorities have agreed to conduct a
joint surveillance plan in the zones where excessive trafficking
has been detected. This emergency plan will include military
action that may need to be taken by the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Miguel Reyes, coordinator of the Nicaraguan Ministry of
Environment and National Resources, said environmental authorities
have inspected the mountainous areas near the borders in order to
find evidence of the occurrence of timber smuggling.
</P>
<P>
Honduras claims its pine timber is being smuggled into the
Nicaraguan North Atlantic autonomous region.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Nicaragua's mahogany and cedar trees are being cut
and allegedly transported from the Bosawa forest reserve to
Honduras. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
