<HEADLINE> Colombia Launches Employment Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Colombia launched a
construction project today as part of the country's social
spending scheme to create more jobs.
</P>
<P>
The project, which will construct 13,000 low-rent houses in the
next six months, will generate more than 60,000 direct jobs, said
President Ernesto Samper from the Presidential House.
</P>
<P>
The project involves housing construction in 12 states for
families earning a monthly income below 845,900 Colombia pesos
(about 680 U.S. dollars), or four times the Colombian minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
The government will put 190 billion pesos (about 152.7 million
dollars) into the project, Samper said.
</P>
<P>
Stressing his government's socially-oriented policy in favor of
the poorest families, Samper said that between August 1994 and
September 1997, his government granted 15,171 houses with an
investment of 190 million dollars, through the National Savings
Fund.
</P>
<P>
The housing policy will be well established within the next 10
years through funds from the private sector and other sectors, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
