<HEADLINE> Tourism Industry Growing in East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, October 9 (Xinhua) -- There were 599,000 overseas
tourists in east China's Fujian province in the first half of this
year, a year-on-year rise of 17.1 percent, according to recent
statistics.
</P>
<P>
A new high was hit in 1996 when the number of tourists was
above a million. Fujian is across the Taiwan Straits from Taiwan
and is the second largest home of overseas Chinese. It has ranked
fourth nationally in major tourism indices for eight consecutive
years, after Guangdong, Beijing, and Shanghai, and tourism has
become one of its pillar industries.
</P>
<P>
Some tourist attractions that appeal most to overseas tourists
are two holiday resorts at Mount Wuyi and Meizhou Island, scenic
Qingyuan Mountain and Taimu Mountain, and Gulangyu Island.
</P>
<P>
In order to improve its tourist attractions and facilities, the
province has worked out a series of preferential policies for
overseas investment. In the first half of the year, it had 328
million US dollars worth of tourism project contracts. To date,
the overseas investment for tourism development is two billion US
dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
