<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Find EB Virus and Breast Cancer Link </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Scientists at a Shanghai tumor
center are saying that, based on research findings, they think
there may be a connection between Epstein-Barr (EB) virus and
breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
A group of researchers at the Shanghai Medical University's
Tumor Hospital, led by Xu Liangzhong, a tumor pathologist, studied
EB virus infection in 102 cases of breast cancer and 47 cases of
benign breast tumor. They found that 28.4 percent of the breast
cancer patients have the EB virus while the rate among those with
benign breast tumors was only 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The research indicated that the EB virus gene and results of
the virus also existed in breast cancer cells and their
reproduction system.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the EB virus exists on a widely scale in the
world, but its mode of transmission has yet not been discovered
here.
</P>
<P>
China has seen a steady growth of the incidence of breast
cancer in the past three years and it now ranks as one of the top
three killers among cancer in women.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971009.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. House Committee Approves Fast-Track Trade Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 8 (Xinhua) -- President Clinton's bid for
negotiating authority to create a free-trade area in West
hemisphere passed a key committee of the U.S. House of
Representatives today with most Democrats rejecting his appeal for
support.
</P>
<P>
The House Ways and Means Committee approved the measure on a
24-14 vote with only four Democrats voting for it.
</P>
<P>
The measure gives the U.S. president the power to negotiate
future free-trade agreements under a "fast-track" process that
requires quick congressional consideration and a yes-or-no vote
without amendments.
</P>
<P>
The legislation that cleared the House committee was a
compromise worked out between Republicans and the administration
and was similar to a measure approved by the Senate Finance
Committee last week.
</P>
<P>
The bill would allow negotiations to ensure that countries
don't seek to lower existing labor and environmental regulations
to gain unfair advantage. But Democratic opponents contended this
did not provide American workers with enough protection against
unfair competition.
</P>
<P>
Clinton met with 10 Democrats in the Ways and Means Committee
Tuesday night to appeal for their votes but only four of them
supported him today.
</P>
<P>
The fast-track process is also strongly opposed by labor
unions, which charge that it opens the way for future trade deals
that will allow U.S. corporations to move more of their factories
to low-wage countries with lax environmental laws.
</P>
<P>
Clinton needs fast-track authority to achieve a key goal of his
second term, preparing the way for a hemisphere-wide free-trade
zone by 2005. The administration has also committed to starting
negotiations to achieve free trade in the Pacific by 2010.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971009.0305 </DOCNO>
