<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Cities Appear in Southeast Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Many modern cities thrive
alongside the Yarlung Zangbo River, southeast of the Tibet
Autonomous Region, stimulating the regional economy.
</P>
<P>
Neat, wide roads have taken place of muddy, bumpy paths. Street
vendors continue their businesses in newly-completed shopping
malls. Broadcasting towers have been built against the backdrop of
the blue sky and snow-topped mountain peaks.
</P>
<P>
The polished appearance is commonplace now in Nyingchi and
Shannan prefectures, which just a few years ago were backward and
remote.
</P>
<P>
For the past year, the local government of Nyingchi has poured
120 million yuan (about 14.4 million US dollars) into road
construction as well as sewage treatment, telecommunications and
other community facilities.
</P>
<P>
Officials of Shannan Prefecture has also earmarked 180 million
yuan (21.7 million US dollars) as infrastructure investment. A
primary school and a hospital were put into use this year.
</P>
<P>
"The improvement of infrastructure conditions has already
brought us profits," said Qian Xianfa, secretary of Gyaca County
Committee of the Chinese Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
"The flourishing service sector is also accelerating the
development of local economy," said Qian, citing that his county's
industrial and commercial tax revenue increased by 58 percent from
the last year.
</P>
<P>
Two years ago, the town of Gyaca had only seven shops -- now
there are 70.
</P>
<P>
Bayi Town in Nyingchi County even sketched out a blueprint for
commercial, industrial development, cultural and living areas.
Local officials said the town will expand to 70 square kilometers
in the future, from the current four square kilometers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
