<HEADLINE> Chinese Jiangxi Delegation Lures Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 8 (Xinhua) -- A high-level trade delegation
from eastern China's Jiangxi Province opened an exhibition in the
World Trade Center here today, with the aim of attracting more
foreign investments to the province.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, headed by the province's vice-governor Huang
Zhiquan, is the province's largest measured by the sizes of the
projects it offers.
</P>
<P>
Huang said at the opening ceremony that Jiangxi, which used to
lag behind its neighbors such as Jiangsu and Zhejiang province,
are catching up these years. The completion of the
Beijing-Kowloon railway, which runs through the province from
north to south, has brought a lot of opportunities to Jiangxi,
Huang said.
</P>
<P>
The province has also improved the foundation of transport and
energy systems, he added.
</P>
<P>
Vaughu Koshkarian, vice-president of the Fort Motor Corp.,
briefed the attendants their success in Jiangsu. The U.S. auto
maker has bought 20 percent of the shares of the Jiangsu Jiangling
Motor Co.. The first Fort designed van is scheduled to roll off
the production line December 2.
</P>
<P>
Jiangxi authorities wish to use the Fort story to gain more
investment. They have brought more than 100 projects with each
needing millions of U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The projects cover wide ranges, including highway construction,
power supply, farming, chemical engineering, metallurgy,
electronics, textiles and tourism. The Guixi Power Plant needs
325 million U.S. dollars to install two 300,000 kw thermal power
generator sets. The Ganbei Chemical Plant is looking for 110
million U.S. dollars to buy technology and key equipment for
producing new products.  
