<HEADLINE> Canadians to Slow Spending Next Year, Board </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Low personal savings and high
debt loads, combined with higher interest rates, will slow the
growth in Canadian household spending next year, an economic
think-tank said today.
</P>
<P>
"The consumer is leading the way in 1997," said Jim Frank,
vice-president and chief economist of the Conference Board of
Canada.
</P>
<P>
"Housing starts are strong, retail sales are rising, and auto
sales are on track for their strongest growth in over a decade,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"With continued stellar job creation, consumer confidence is at
an eight-year high," Frank said while releasing the board's
Canadian Outlook for this Autumn.
</P>
<P>
The board forecasts a 3.4 percent HDP growth for Canada this
year and 3.1 percent growth in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Though income prospects for next year are better than at any
time this decade, interest rates are expected to rise by 50 basis
points over the next few months, according to the board.
</P>
<P>
"With total consumer debt now exceeding 96 percent of
disposable income, rising interest rates will make personal
debt-servicing costs more onerous," Frank noted.
</P>
<P>
Yet, strong wage gains and moderate inflation will help lift
real personal disposable income to 2.6 percent next year, the best
performance in eight years, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
