<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Stocks fell sharply today as
Alan Greenspan dampened investor optimism with another warning
about inflationary pressures and market exuberance.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average was down 83.25 points to
8,095.06.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a nearly 2-to-1
margin on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 572.29
million shares as against 551.41 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 9.28 to 973.84, and
the NYSE composite index fell 4.64 to 509.57, but the Nasdaq
composite index rose 4.50 to 1,741.77.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 slipped 0.12 to 463.66, and the American Stock
Exchange composite index fell 3.60 to 718.30, snapping a string of
seven closing highs by measure, which is dominated by smaller
companies.
</P>
<P>
Broad-market indicators also sank as the latest congressional
testimony by Federal Reserve chairman Greenspan pulled down the
bond market which rallied recently.
</P>
<P>
Greenspan, warning that the current economic good times could
be cut short if inflationary pressures emerge, told the House
Budget Committee that it may be only a matter of time until tight
labor markets force wages higher.
</P>
<P>
As bond prices fell, the yield on the 30-year Treasury rose as
high as 6.36 percent from late Tuesday's 6.23 percent, which was
it's lowest finish since February 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
