<HEADLINE> World Bank Backs Honduras' Mesoamerican Biological </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank today
announced the approval of a 7 million U.S. dollar Trust Fund Grant
to Honduras to help finance the Biodiversity in Priority Areas
Project.
</P>
<P>
The project is initiated by the Global Environment Facility
(GEF) as a bid to protect and conserve the delicate biodiversity
of the Honduran section of the Mesoamerican Biological Corridor,
which is also known as the "Path of the Jaguar".
</P>
<P>
This is also a joint project by the World Bank and the United
Nations Development program (UNDP), which is setting a new legal
precedence for collaboration by the two institutions.
</P>
<P>
Eleven areas in four geographic groupings of Honduras will be
included in the conservation and protection efforts of the
project.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the project is estimated at 9.5 million
dollars. In addition to the World Bank grant, 2.2 million dollars
are from the Honduran government and the remaining from the
beneficiaries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
