<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Again Fails to Break Campaign Overhaul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate Wednesday
again failed to break a Republican filibuster holding up action on
a bill designed to revise campaign finance rules.
</P>
<P>
That 52-47 vote was eight short of the 60 needed to end debate
and proceed with the measure. Majority Republicans declared it
dead after a nearly identical vote on the bill Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Today's vote was part of a move by Democrats to keep pressing
the issue.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the vote, Senate Republican leader Trent Lott flatly
declared the measure "dead," saying its proposed ban on
unregulated "soft" political donations contradicts the Supreme
Court's finding that such funds are a protected form of free
speech. "Soft" donations, used for generic party activities,
differ from "hard" contributions, which are used to back a
particular campaign and which the court says can be restricted.
</P>
<P>
Lott said that the legislation "is not going to going to pass."
</P>
<P>
Lott called it "a diversionary tactic," and that Democrats are
trying to shift attention away from questions about fund-raising
in President Bill Clinton's re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
Democrats said Republicans are defending a system favoring
Republicans.  
</P>
</TEXT>
