<HEADLINE> 538 PKK Rebels Killed in Turkish Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- A total of 538 rebels of the
outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) have been killed in the
Turkish military operation in northern Iraq since late last
month, the Anatolia News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that figures issued by the Turkish General
Staff show that nine PKK militants were captured and 12 others
surrendered to the Turkish troops in the operation.
</P>
<P>
However, the Turkish General Staff failed to mention the
casualties of the Turkish troops.
</P>
<P>
Late last month, around 15,000 Turkish troops, backed by jets
and artillery fire, launched a cross-border operation in northern
Iraq aimed at smashing newly-built PKK camps there.
</P>
<P>
In the operation, Turkish Air Force jets bombed 15 PKK camps
near the Iranian and Syrian borders.
</P>
<P>
Describing the PKK as a threat to Turkey's border security,
Turkish Foreign Ministry said earlier that the Turkish military
had the right to take such actions to defend state interests.
</P>
<P>
Last May, Turkey sent as many as 50,000 troops into northern
Iraq in a massive cross-border operation, dealing a heavy blow on
the PKK rebels.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing Turkish military operation has triggered severe
criticism from Iran and some Arab countries, which accused Ankara
of violating Iraq's sovereignty and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a 13-year-old war against the
Turkish authorities for the establishment of an independent
Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
