<HEADLINE> Free Banking Urged for GCC Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The six-member Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) is considering to allow banks of each
GCC country operate in the other member countries.
</P>
<P>
Central bank and monetary institution chiefs of GCC members
today put forward the recommendation for each GCC country to
license the operation of bank branches of other members.
</P>
<P>
The bank governors, who just concluded their 25th meeting in
Riyadh, Saudi Arabia, have referred the recommendation to the GCC
economic and foreign ministers for approval, according to Kuwait
News Agency reports from Riyadh.
</P>
<P>
The Qatari Central Bank governor and chairman of the
governors' meeting Abdullah Al-Ateyya said the measures would
serve the objective to open GCC banking branches sought by the
member states in order to achieve the unified economic agreement
advocated since the founding of the GCC in 1981.
</P>
<P>
GCC groups Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, the United Arab Emirates,
Oman, Qatar and Bahrain. Kuwait and Qatar have successfully linked
their banks' auto tellers.
</P>
<P>
Al-Ateyya expressed hope that the rest of the GCC member states
would join and complete such GCC bank-net, saying such step would
expand banking services for the interests of the GCC citizens.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kuwaiti Central Bank governor Sheikh Salem Abdel
Aziz Al-Sabah expressed belief that the GCC countries would be
able to join the Kuwait-Qatar network within two years.
</P>
<P>
Just a number of technical obstacles are hindering the linkage of
network among the GCC countries, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971009.0328 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Calls on to Promote an Ethos of Disaster Prevention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 8 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan today called on all states to intensify their work of
promoting an ethos of disaster prevention in order to build a
safer world for the twenty-first century.
</P>
<P>
Addressing on the occasion of International day for Natural
Disaster Reduction, October 8, the UN chief said this year's
observation shined a spotlight on the role of water in natural
disasters. Earthquakes, cyclones and volcanic eruptions may be
among the most dramatic natural hazards, but water-lated disasters
-- from floods and drought to desertification -- affected more
people and caused more damage. The focus on water was especially
timely.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General said floods were occurring more
frequently than other disasters, a trend attributable to many
causes, including deforestation and rapid development, especially
in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
Annan said but drought and desertification were also on the
rise. Drought was also a leading killer, causing the deaths of a
reported 74,000 people in 1976. Desertification were affecting one
fourth of the earth's land and more than one billion of the
world's people, and cost 42 billion U.S. dollars each year in lost
productivity.
</P>
<P>
He said deforestation was a major contributing factor, along
with other poor land use practice such as overgrazing,
over-cultivation and mismanagement of irrigation.
</P>
<P>
Annan said the United Nations was fully engaged in efforts to
help countries cope with natural disasters and incorporate
disaster reduction and preparedness into their overall development
plans. In 1989, as a spur to international action and cooperation,
the General Assembly proclaimed the International Decade for
Natural Disaster Reduction (1990-2000). Throughout the 1990s,
United Nations conferences on the environment, pollution, human
settlements and other issues stressed the links between disaster
reduction and sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
The UN chief said since the World Conference on Natural
Disaster Deduction held in 1994 in Japan, many countries had
adopted new laws and national strategies for disaster reduction,
preparedness and mitigation. The United Nations, for its part, had
carried out disaster management training programs in dozens of
countries, focusing on institution-building, early warning,
network between institutions and individuals, and the production
and dissemination of training materials.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General said that when disaster stroke, the
Organization arranged for relief shipments, launched international
appeals for assistance and served as a clearinghouse for
information about needs and consequences.
</P>
<P>
He said the world was facing a paradox with water-lated
disasters: too much water, and too little. Virtually every country
was facing the prospect of both flood and water shortage. Such
disasters knew no borders. Floods and droughts often affected
several countries at once.
</P>
<P>
He called for international cooperation to reduce the loss of
life, property damage, and economic and social disruptions caused
by natural disasters and environmental emergencies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971009.0329 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Apologizes Again Over Attack in Jordan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu phoned Jordanian King Hussein this evening,
apologizing again over the Israeli agents' attack on a Hamas
leader last month in Amman, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said he was really sorry that the incident has
caused so much trouble and damage to the Israeli-Jordanian
relations and pledged that Israel will do its best to improve the
relationship and cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Under a Hussein-brokered bargain, the two Israeli agents who
attacked Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas) leader Khaled Mashaal
last month in Amman were released in exchange for the release of
Hamas founder Sheikh Ahmed Yassin, who was jailed by Israel in
1989 for ordering attacks by Hamas guerrillas against Israeli
targets.
</P>
<P>
Israel also freed Tuesday nine Jordanian detainees in Israel in
a bid to improve its ties with Jordan, which went strained
following the failed attack.
</P>
<P>
Jordan was one of the two Arab countries to sign peace
treaties with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein said in Amman today that he had told Israel two
days before the attack that Hamas is willing to have a truce with
Israel.
</P>
<P>
However, Netanyahu told Hussein that he received the message
only after the attack, otherwise, the incident would not occur,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli prime minister has appointed a three-member
committee to probe this incident.
</P>
<P>
But the Israeli opposition parties, including the Labor Party,
have stepped up their attack on Netanyahu for authorizing such a
attack in a friendly country.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parties are calling for a state inquiry headed
by a judge with authority to subpoena witnesses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
